Analysing ESG report using Natural Language Processing¶

Summary¶

Environment, Social and Corporate Governance (ESG) refers to the three central factors in measuring the sustainability and societal impact of an investment in a company or business. These criteria help to better determin the future financial performance of companies (return and risk).

This analysis extracts text from a ESG report in PDF format from the internet, performs NLP on these information, summaries the key ESG initiatives with WordClouds, TDIDFs and discovers topics by building a Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA) model.

Given that ESG is a broad topic. Different companies focus on different aspects of ESG depending on their business operations and culture. One can potentially ingest more ESG reports from different companies across all sectors and industries to capture relevant ESG topics. This to be attempted in another analysis.

import sys

def CreateFolder(in_dir):
    print('创建'+in_dir+'文件夹')
    isExists=os.path.exists(in_dir)
    if not isExists: #不存在则创建
        print('创建'+in_dir+'文件夹成功')
    else:
        print(in_dir+'文件夹已存在')
CreateFolder(DATA_FOLDER)

Report Details¶

Enter required information about the report. Report must be in PDF format and downloadable from a URL.

  1. Company Name
  2. Company Ticker Symbol
  3. Year of the Report
  4. URL of the Report

Text Extraction¶

Extract information from the PDF report. This process may take some time. Do be patient.

You may skip to the last step of this section if you have previously extracted the contents and stored in a json file.

In [16]:
def extract_pdf(file, verbose=False):
    
    if verbose:
        print('Processing {}'.format(file))

    try:
        resource_manager = PDFResourceManager()
        fake_file_handle = io.StringIO()
        codec = 'utf-8'
        laparams = LAParams()

        converter = TextConverter(resource_manager, fake_file_handle, codec=codec, laparams=laparams)
        page_interpreter = PDFPageInterpreter(resource_manager, converter)
        
        password = ""
        maxpages = 0
        caching = True
        pagenos = set()

        content = []

        for page in PDFPage.get_pages(file,
                                      pagenos, 
                                      maxpages=maxpages,
                                      password=password,
                                      caching=True,
                                      check_extractable=False):

            page_interpreter.process_page(page)

            content.append(fake_file_handle.getvalue())

            fake_file_handle.truncate(0)
            fake_file_handle.seek(0)        

        text = '##PAGE_BREAK##'.join(content)

        # close open handles
        converter.close()
        fake_file_handle.close()
        
        return text

    except Exception as e:
        print(e)

        # close open handles
        converter.close()
        fake_file_handle.close()

        return ""
In [17]:
def extract_content(url):
    """
    A simple user define function that, given a url, download PDF text content
    Parse PDF and return plain text version
    """
    headers={"User-Agent":"Mozilla/5.0"}

    try:
        # retrieve PDF binary stream
        r = requests.get(url, allow_redirects=True, headers=headers)
        
        # access pdf content
        text = extract_pdf(io.BytesIO(r.content))

        # return concatenated content
        return text

    except:
        return ""

report_content = extract_content(report_url)

Kent Masters, Chairman, President and Chief Executive Officer \nThe world now finds itself \nmore than two years into the \npandemic. What impact did \nthe ongoing challenges of \nCOVID-19 have on Albemarle \nin 2021? \nWe did not anticipate that the pandemic \nwould be with us for as long as it has, but \nI’m proud to say that, as an organization, \nwe’ve shown great agility and resilience \nin our ability to adapt. As a values-driven \ncompany focused on health and safety, \nour employees continued to stay vigilant \nin terms of safety protocols to protect \nthemselves, their colleagues, and our \ncommunities. Despite the headwinds we \nfaced in 2021 around remote working, \nlabor shortages at some sites, and supply \nchain interruptions, we maintained \nbusiness continuity and were able to serve \nour customers with minimal disruption. \nThis is a testament to the dedication \nand commitment of our people and the \nstrength of our values and purpose that \nmake Albemarle a leader in our industry. \n\nWhat are some 2021 \nhighlights? \nIn 2021, we rolled out the Albemarle \nWay of Excellence, our operating model \nfor executing against our strategy and \naccelerating sustainability. It helps us \nbalance our four strategic pillars to grow \nprofitably, maximize productivity, invest \nwith discipline, and advance sustainability \nwith the goals of driving greater \nstakeholder value, delivering outstanding \ncustomer service, and raising the bar \non excellence. Despite the pandemic, \n2021 was very much a growth year for \nAlbemarle. Our strong balance sheet, \nhealthy margins, and increased equity \nfrom the ~$1.5 billion equity raise we \ncompleted early in the year, gave us the \ncapital to execute on our growth strategy \nand to make significant investments in \nsustainability. We completed construction \nof a thermal evaporator at our La Negra \nsite in Chile, which allows us to double \nour lithium production without a \ncorresponding increase in freshwater \nuse. Working closely with partners in \nthe electric vehicle (EV) supply chain, \nwe continued to invest in technology for \nlithium-ion battery recycling, which will \nbe key as we progress towards a more \ncircular economy. We also enhanced \nour organizational structure to best \nserve our business interests and needs \nglobally. We created key, senior level \npositions including Albemarle’s first Vice \nPresident of Global Government and \n\nCommunity Affairs and Chief Supply \nChain Officer. Both positions speak to \nthe importance we’re placing on ensuring \nour license to operate around the world \nand the significance of driving business \nand sustainability excellence throughout \nour value chain. We also continued to \nengage in sustainability on the global \nstage by becoming a participant in the \nUnited Nations Global Compact (UNGC), \na 15,000 strong network of peers that \nspans 165 countries and which aims to \nalign corporate strategies and operations \nwith universal principles on human rights, \nlabor, environment, and anti-corruption.\n\nWhy is sustainability \nimportant to Albemarle’s \nbusiness success? \nOur business plays an important role in \ncombating climate change and helping \nthe world transition to a green economy. \nOur products and services make the world \nsafer and more sustainable, and we pride \nourselves on doing the right things, the \nright way, with the right resources. With \nsustainability firmly embedded in our \nstrategy, we continue to add value for \nall stakeholders. Our customers want to \nwork with a partner who is aligned with \ntheir values and is producing products \nin a sustainable way. In an increasingly \ncompetitive marketplace for talent, our \nsustainability commitments are a clear \ndifferentiator, and we know that current \n\nJ. In 2022, \nwe will drive forward our investment in \nour people through enhanced training \nand development opportunities and by \ncontinuing to foster a diverse workforce, \nan equitable workplace, and an inclusive \nculture where everyone can reach their \nfull potential. There is still work to be \ndone, but I am confident that we have  \nthe right strategy, the right people,  \nand the right tools in place to succeed.  \nWe have charted our sustainability  \ncourse, and we’re ready to execute  \non our commitments. \n\nand prospective employees want to work \nfor a company that is demonstrating \nleadership in this area. Our shareholders \nare also increasingly incorporating \nsustainability into their investment \ndecisions. We continue to see our efforts \npaying off. For the sixth consecutive year, \nEcoVadis, a leading sustainability ratings \nagency, has awarded Albemarle gold \nmedal status. This recognition places us  \nin the top six percent of more than \n75,000 companies worldwide. \n\nFinally, what can we expect \nfrom Albemarle in 2022? \nWe’re now firmly grounded in our \napproach to sustainability investments \nand activities that generate long-term \nvalue for all our stakeholders, and we’re \nmaking substantial progress towards \nour sustainability goals. In 2022, we \nset additional ambitious sustainability \ntargets for diversity. We plan on \ncompleting life cycle assessments  \n(LCAs) for more of our products to \naccount for their full impact on the \nenvironment. – OUR BUSINESS SEGMENTS \nAs a leader in the specialty chemicals industry, we serve our customers through our three GBUs.\n\nLITHIUM – ENABLING THE EV REVOLUTION\n\nAlbemarle is an industry leader in battery, \nindustrial, and specialty grade, high-quality \nlithium production. We operate across \na diverse range of hard rock and brine \nlithium resources and conversion facilities \nin Europe, North and South America, Asia, \nand Australia, to develop and manufacture \na broad range of lithium compounds, \nincluding lithium carbonate, lithium \nhydroxide, lithium chloride, and value-\nadded lithium specialties and reagents.\n\nIn 2021, we accelerated our Lithium \ngrowth strategy. We reached mechanical \ncompletion of La Negra III/IV and  \nKemerton I, in Chile and Australia, \nrespectively. We also announced the signing \nof agreements in China to acquire all the \noutstanding equity of Tianyuan, a company \nwhose operations include a recently \nconstructed lithium conversion plant in \nQinzhou, and investment agreements to \nbuild greenfield lithium conversion plants.\n\nOur lithium production is focused on \nminimizing environmental and social \nimpact and maximizing stakeholder \nbenefit. We do this in a myriad of ways, \nincluding managing our carbon footprint \nand reducing GHG emissions:\n• \n\n Passive solar energy is the most \nsustainable and cost-effective way \nto concentrate brine and makes \nup about 80% of Albemarle’s total \nenergy consumption\n Our Kemerton plant in Australia \nis expected to use ~35% green \nelectricity by 2023, with plans in \nplace to reach net-zero 2050 for \nenergy use\n La Negra and Salar de Atacama plan \nto move to solar powered electricity \nby 2025\n Electric forklifts are used in \noperations at Langelsheim, Germany\n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\n“ The lithium market is expected to see significant demand growth in the coming years. As an industry leader, \nwe will drive sustainability forward by continuing to lead by example, helping to define the standards of \nsustainable lithium production, and by maintaining focus on the wellbeing of the communities where we live \nand operate. At Albemarle, how we produce lithium is as important as how much we produce.”\n– Eric Norris, President, Lithium\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n15\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##LITHIUM GLOBAL SNAPSHOT\n\nChengdu, \nChina\n\nLithium Financials\n\n$1.4B\n\nNet Sales\n\n$480M\n\nAdjusted EBITDA1\n\n35%\n\nAdjusted EBITDA Margin1\n\n Note: Financials for the 12 months ended December 31, 2021.\n\n¹  Non-GAAP measure. Our fire safety \ntechnology enables the use of plastics  \nin high-heat applications by enhancing \ntheir flame-resistant properties. We have  \na diverse portfolio of brominated fire \nsafety solutions that are used in a breadth \nof consumer and industrial products  \nand processes, including 5G infrastructure, \nhome electronics, appliances, computers, \nsmartphones, building insulation,  \nand automobiles, including EVs.\n\nWith a focus on improving productivity and \nsustainability, our Bromine business boasts \nseveral important programs including:\n• \n\n Waste heat integration projects at \nJordan Bromine Company (JBC)\n Waste evaporation pond elimination \nat JBC\n Recycling of water from artificial \nmarsh outfall with a 20% reduction \nin aquifer loading\n Process integration program \nconverting waste stream containing \nsignificant water into a value-added \nfeedstock with 11% water intensity \nreduction and 6% energy intensity \nreduction\n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\nDuring 2021, our Bromine business \nsuccessfully completed a resource \nexpansion in Arkansas and a \ndebottlenecking project in Jordan, both  \non budget and on, or ahead of schedule.\n\n“ The Bromine business is a global market leader and the markets we are serving are growing rapidly. Our \ncustomized FCC catalysts systems assist in \nhigh yield cracking of refinery petroleum \nstreams into derivative, higher-value \nproducts such as transportation fuels and \npetrochemical feedstocks like propylene. \n\nOur HPC and FCC catalysts also allow \nrefineries to run at lower temperatures, \nthereby saving costs and reducing  \nGHG emissions. \n\n“ Our Catalysts business has a comprehensive strategy to take advantage of key growth opportunities in crude-\nto-chemicals, emerging markets, and renewables and recycling application. These areas for growth are firmly \naligned with our technology strengths and with our customers. As previously announced, we are undertaking a \nstrategic review of our Catalysts business to maximize value and ensure the ongoing success of the business.”\n– Raphael Crawford, President, Catalysts\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n19\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##CATALYSTS GLOBAL SNAPSHOT\n\nAmsterdam, \nThe Netherlands\n\nCatalysts Financials\n\n$761M\n\nNet Sales\n\n$107M\n\nAdjusted EBITDA1\n\n14%\n\nAdjusted EBITDA Margin1\n\n Note: Financials for the 12 months ended December 31, 2021.\n\n¹  Non-GAAP measure. For example, \nthis report includes our initial scope 3 \ngreenhouse gas assessment. This year we \nengaged PricewaterhouseCoopers (PwC) to \nperform an attest review engagement over \ncertain of our total energy consumption \nand scope 1 and 2 greenhouse gas \nemissions metrics. See PwC’s Report of \nIndependent Accountants on page 105. In \ncoming years, we plan to obtain assurance \nover additional sustainability data.\n\nWe hope that as you read this report \nyou will see that Albemarle continues to \naccelerate our sustainability efforts and \nthat we remain committed to industry \nleading sustainability practices and \nperformance. Thank you for following \nour sustainability journey, and we look \nforward to sharing our progress now and in \nthe future.\n\nWe are proud of how our company has \naccelerated sustainability initiatives and \nresults over the past year, and we continue \nto drive our strategy forward with bold \nambitions and new targets. In our 2021 \nreport, we are introducing new targets for \ndiversity, equity and inclusion (DE&I). For \nDE&I, our first goal is to increase global \ngender diversity by 1% per year with a \nparticular focus on our manufacturing \nworkforce; our second goal is to increase \nU.S. racial diversity by 1% per year in \nsenior-level management roles. In both \ncases, our aim is to increase diversity \nsteadily and consistently with the long-\nterm goal of meeting or exceeding global \nmanufacturing benchmarks.\n\nIn last year’s report, we introduced our \ninitial sustainability targets as seen in the \ntable to the right. In 2021, our work focused \non designing and executing a portfolio \nof projects to achieve these goals and \nbuilding the infrastructure necessary to \ntrack our progress. In 2022, we are building \nthese targets into the Objectives and Key \nResults (OKRs) for our Executive Leadership \nTeam (ELT) and cascading them through \nthe organization. We are also building \ninternal capabilities to track greenhouse \ngas emissions and freshwater use based on \npreliminary monthly data to ensure greater \ntransparency and coordination across our \noperations and corporate functions. \n\nThis report details several important \norganizational changes designed to \nstrengthen our sustainability performance \nand capabilities. In 2021, we clarified Board \noversight of sustainability and updated \ncommittee charters to reflect these changes. \nWe also created the role of Chief Supply \nChain Officer (CSCO) to enable end-to-end \nsupply chain optimization and traceability. \nFinally, we created a Global Government \nand Community Affairs team to be more \nconsistent in our approach to community \nengagement across DEVELOPMENT GOALS\nThe United Nations Sustainable Development Goals (UNSDGs) are a blueprint \nto achieve a better and more sustainable future.\nThey address global environmental and \nsocial challenges, including poverty, \ninequality, climate change, and \nenvironmental degradation. Companies \naround the world are encouraged to align \ntheir strategies and business activities with \nthe UNSDGs. In 2020, we mapped our \ncorporate and sustainability priorities, core \nvalues, material topics, and strategic focus \nareas within Albemarle to nine SDG goals. \nWe also identified opportunities for the \nway in which our products, services, and \ncommunity engagement work contribute \nto the advancement of the goals and \nwhere the opportunities for the greatest \nsustainability impact lie for Albemarle.\n\nWe responsibly manage our use \nof resources and materials.\n\nWe are committed to building an inclusive and \ndiverse workplace. We promote collaboration and \nengage in the communities where we work and live.\n\nIn 2021, we became a signatory to the \nUnited Nations Global Compact (UNGC). \nWith over 15,000 member companies \naround the globe, the UNGC is the \nworld’s largest sustainability initiative \nand network. It represents a call to action \nfor companies to align strategies and \noperations with 10 universal principles \nfocused on human rights, labor, \nenvironment, and anti-corruption, and  \nto take actions that advance societal  \ngoals. This year’s sustainability report \nserves as our annual Communication on \nProgress (COP), a key commitment of  \nour UNGC membership. \n\nWe foster the conditions that create sustainable, \nlong-term value for our shareholders and stakeholders.\n\n“ We are pleased to continue our support of the UN Global Compact and to report our progress \nin this year’s sustainability report. The UN Global Compact principles align well with \nAlbemarle’s core values, culture, and the way we do business.”\n– Kent Masters, Albemarle Chairman, President and CEO\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n28\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##STAKEHOLDER ENGAGEMENT \nAt Albemarle, we recognize that our license to operate is dependent upon effective and ongoing \nstakeholder engagement. We pride ourselves on developing and maintaining relationships built  \non trust, transparency, and open communication.\nEmployees\nAlbemarle regularly communicates \nwith our employees regarding company \ninitiatives, news, goals, and performance. \nWe do this through daily updates to \nAlbert, our company intranet, and \nfrequent updates to our corporate website, \nquarterly town hall meetings hosted by \nour CEO and GBUs that are recorded and \nposted to Albert, written memos, and \nin-person meetings (where possible). \nThroughout the COVID-19 pandemic, \nwe increased communications with our \nemployees through Albert while many \npeople were working remotely. We \nestablished a dedicated webpage to our \npandemic response, dispensing information \non safety protocols for on-site employees, \ncase counts, information on vaccinations, \nand other relevant information. \n\nGovernment and Regulators\nAlbemarle employees responsible for \nmanaging government and regulatory \naffairs consistently engage with \ngovernments and regulators via phone, \nemail, or in-person meetings (when \npossible). The Albemarle Corporation \nPolitical Action Committee (Albemarle \nPAC) supports federal candidates who have \ndemonstrated support for the principles to \nwhich the Company is dedicated. Political \ncontributions are funded by voluntary \ncontributions from eligible employees. \n\nShareholder/Investment \nCommunity\nRegular updates are provided primarily \nthrough our SEC filings, publicly available \nquarterly earnings calls, and other \npresentations to industry and investor \ngroups that are webcast and available for \nviewing on our website. We also co-host \nanalyst events, attend conferences, and \nconduct direct outreach to address investor \nconcerns and answer questions.\n\nNGOs\nWe engage with global, regional, and \nnational NGOs on environmental, social, \nand governance issues to demonstrate \nthe benefits of our products and the \nsustainable operation of our facilities. \n\nMedia\nAlbemarle routinely distributes press \nreleases and conducts interviews with \nrelevant media to ensure accurate and \nconsistent external messaging and to \nfurther engage with trade associations, \nregulators, customers, and other key \nstakeholder groups.\n\nIndustry and Trade \nAssociations\nAlbemarle participates in trade and \nindustry associations globally, such as \nthe American Chemistry Council. We \ncollaborate with global trade associations \nto conduct and publish peer-reviewed, \nscientific research, and we make these \nstudies available to government agencies \nand other interested parties. We regularly \nreview new and existing association \nmemberships to ensure they align with our \nstrategy and values. In 2021, we became \na founding member of the International \nLithium Association. For a list of our \nassociations please see our website.\n\nFollowing the violence at the U.S. \nCapitol on Jan. 6, 2021, we suspended \ncontributions pending a review of our \npolitical contribution policy. Based on \nthe outcome of this review, we expect to \namend our policy in 2022. First, we will \nconsider character, ethics, reputation, and \nvoting record in support of democratic \nprocesses. We also plan to enhance our \ndiligence to ensure candidates to whom \nwe contribute are aligned with our values \nand interests. Finally, we plan to monitor \nour industry associations’ political \ncontributions to ensure they are aligned \nwith our policies and relevant regulations. \nFor more information on our political \ncontributions, please see our website.\n\nOur Employee Resource Groups (ERGs), \ncalled CONNECT groups, also play a key \nrole in sharing important information \nwith our global workforce. Additionally, \nemployees can ask business-related \nquestions any time via a dedicated \nemail address. \n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n29\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##NATURAL \nRESOURCE  \nMANAGEMENT\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n30\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##ENERGY AND EMISSIONS\nAt Albemarle, our goal is to be as efficient as possible in \nmanaging our natural resources to support our growth in \na sustainable manner. We pride ourselves on producing \nproducts that play a critical role in the reduction of \nGHG emissions; however, we are also keenly aware \nof the impact that our energy-intensive operations \nhave on the environment. In 2021, we established and \nbegan executing our Climate Strategy with an ambition \nto be net-zero in our operations by 2050. We aim to \nachieve this through a reduction in our overall energy \nconsumption by working towards optimal energy \nefficiency in our operations and by purchasing energy \nfrom renewable sources where possible. \nMeasuring Our Energy Use and Emissions\nWe identify, measure, and calculate the \nGHG emissions of our manufacturing \noperations, including production, non-\nproduction, joint ventures and leased/\nowned vehicles, by considering the \nprinciples and guidance of the GHG \nProtocol Corporate Standard. We \nimplemented a corporate-wide scope 1 \nand 2 GHG data collection system in \n2020. In 2021, we engaged PwC to \nperform an attest review engagement \nover certain of our 2021 total energy \nconsumption and scope 1 and scope 2 \nGHG emissions metrics. See PwC’s Report \nof Independent Accountants on page 105. \nThe organizational boundaries, emission \nfactors, and additional information on \nour methodology are detailed in the \nmanagement assertion letter. \n\nIn late 2021, we also began our initial \nassessment of our scope 3 GHG emissions. \nAlbemarle has identified 12 relevant \nscope 3 categories with purchased goods \nand services, upstream and downstream \ntransportation, fuel- and energy-related \nactivities, end-of-life treatment, and \ninvestments being the most relevant for \nour business. We will continue to refine \nour assessment in the coming years, and \nwe will use our initial assessment to work \nwith customers and suppliers to reduce \nemissions across the supply chain.\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n31\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Energy Efficiency \nThe “Heartbeat Project,” in our Amsterdam \nproduction facility, alludes to the fact \nthat without steam, we cannot run our \nplants. This initiative involved replacing an \noutdated steam boiler and compressed air \nutility plant that had become inefficient \nand obsolete with a new system that \nuses innovative heat recovery and heat \nintegration technology to capture heat \nfrom the compressed air production. \nThe heat is recovered in the form of \nwater from which the steam is then \ncreated. This project has reduced our \nenergy consumption at our Amsterdam \nproduction facility by 2.5%\n\nAlso at our Amsterdam production facility, \nafter drying slurries in the FCC unit we \ntypically further calcine the material at \nvery high temperatures. This treatment \nprocess requires the use of a large amount \nof natural gas and generates hot air that \nis typically released into the environment. \nMany years ago, a heat integration \nprocess was designed for the facility to \nre-utilize the released heat, but it was \nnever operationalized due to technical \nissues. Thanks to newly developed process \ncontrols that make the operation more \nreliable, we are now able to activate this \nclosed loop heat cycle. The technical teams \nin Amsterdam continue to work on further \nheat reduction efforts.\n\nIn 2021, we entered a partnership with \nSchneider Electric to help us manage our \nglobal energy procurement and negotiate \npower purchase agreements (PPAs). \nSchneider Electric provides companies such \nas Albemarle with energy and automation \ndigital solutions for the efficient and \nsustainable day-to-day management of \nenergy supply.\n\nLooking to the future, we plan to install a \nthermal oxidizer at our Taiwan facility. This \nwill be a combustion system that prevents \nvolatile organic compounds (VOCs) from \nbeing released into the air. Like the process \nalready underway at our Amsterdam \nproduction facility, we are also pursuing \nenergy-recovery projects in our Kings \nMountain drying process, which would \nreduce scope 1 emissions.\n\nWhile there are environmental benefits \nattributable to these initiatives, there \nare also financial advantages. As a global \norganization, we face imbalanced energy \ncosts and are subject to legislation \ngoverning emissions such as carbon taxes \nin certain jurisdictions. This can lead to \na high level of unpredictability in our \ninput cost management. By introducing \ninnovative process technology that helps \nus save on energy consumption, we can \nmitigate the financial implications of \nthese rising costs and prepare for future \nregulatory changes.\n\nIn accordance with the GHG Protocol, our scope 3 \nassessment does not include negative or avoided \nemissions. Our lithium products facilitate the global \ntransition to clean energy. Based on a well-to-wheels \nassessment by IEA, the avoidance of GHG emissions \ndue to the substitution of internal combustion engine \n(ICE) vehicles by electric vehicles (EVs) was 53 million \nmt CO2e for the global EV fleet in 2019. This implies \nthat for every kilogram of GHG emitted during the \nproduction of lithium more than 50 kg of GHG is \nannually avoided during the use of the EV.1 This builds \nup over the lifetime of the battery.\n\nAlbemarle Wins American \nChemistry Council Energy \nEfficiency Award\n\nAfter analyzing data at our lithium carbonate plant in Silver Peak, NV, our team found \nthat steam usage was very high. Further investigation found a level transmitter on a water \ntank failing intermittently, which led to overflows. The level transmitter was replaced \nwith improved technology, resulting in savings of nearly 70,000 gallons of propane and a \nreduction of 400 mt CO2/yr.\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n32\n\n1  Net and avoided well-to-wheel GHG emissions from the global electric vehicle fleet in the Stated Policies Scenario, 2020–2030 – Charts – Data & Statistics – IEA.\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Renewable Energy \nIncreasing our use of renewable energy is an integral part of how we are working towards \nour ambition of net-zero carbon emissions by 2050. Examples of how we use renewable \nenergy in 2021 include:\n• \n\n Passive solar energy, which makes up 80% of Albemarle’s total energy \nconsumption, is used at our Salar de Atacama and Silver Peak production facilities \nto concentrate lithium brines\n Our Amsterdam production facility bought certificates for 100% renewable \nhydroelectricity from Norway\n At our Kemerton production facility in Western Australia, we negotiated a PPA for \nsolar energy that is expected to come online in 2023 and represent up to 30% of \nour energy usage at the production facility. We are also looking at PPAs for our \nSilver Peak, Kings Mountain, and Chilean locations.\n For our Talison joint venture in Australia, we have signed an electricity supply \nagreement with East Rockingham Waste to Energy who harness energy from \nmunicipal and industrial waste diverted from landfills\n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\n2021 Performance \nOur energy consumption (excluding passive solar energy) in 2021 was 13.8 million \ngigajoules (GJ), up 2.1% compared to 2020. Energy consumption decreased in Catalysts \ndue to efficiency projects and lower production, offset by increases in Lithium and \nBromine due to higher production. Approximately 80% of the total energy used in 2021 \nwas passive solar energy. The remaining 13.8 million GJ energy use consists of fossil fuels \nsuch as natural gas, liquid petroleum gas (LPG), gasoline, distillates, and fuel oil (78%) and \ngrid electricity and steam (22%). Approximately 16% of the grid electricity is renewable.\n\nEnergy Use1\n\n6,000,000\n\n5,000,000\n\n4,000,000\n\n3,000,000\n\nJ\n\nG\n\n2,000,000\n\n1,000,000\n\n0\n\n1  Excluding passive solar.\n\nBromine\n\nCatalysts\n\nLithium\n\nOther\n\n2019\n2020\n2021\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n33\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Total scope 1 and 2 GHG emissions were 899 thousand metric tons CO2e (kt CO2e) in 2021, \ndown 3.8% year-on-year. As a result, we can confidently declare that we are on \ntrack to achieve these targets. \n\nCombined GHG emissions for Catalysts and Bromine decreased to 591 kt CO2e in 2021, \nbelow the WB2C reduction scenario of the Science Based Targets (SBT). This reduction was \ndriven primarily by reduced Catalysts’ production, procurement of green electricity, and \ninvestments in scope 1 reductions as better heat integration (as detailed earlier).\n\nIn Lithium, 2021 GHG intensity was 2.8 kg CO2e per kg product, below the stated target of \n3.0 kg CO2e per kg product. The primary driver of this improvement was greener electricity \nmix via renewable contracts, power purchase agreements (PPAs) and investments in local \nsolar energy installations. We are also improving the energy efficiency of new plants and \nseeking incremental energy efficiencies for existing plants. \n\nCatalysts + Bromine GHG Emissions\n\nLithium GHG Intensity\n\ne\n2\nO\nC\n \nt\nk\n\n700\n\n650\n\n600\n\n550\n\n500\n\n450\n\n400\n\n9\n5\n6\n\n8\n1\n6\n\n1\n9\n5\n\n2019 2020 2021 2022 2023 2024 2025 2026 2027 2028 2029 2030\n\n \n\nt\nc\nu\nd\no\nr\np\ng\nk\n/\ne\n2\nO\nC\ng\nk\n\n3.0\n\n2.5\n\n2.0\n\n9\n2\n\n.\n\n9\n2\n\n.\n\n8\n2\n\n.\n\n2019\n\n2020\n\n2021\n\nTotal GHG\n2030 Target (SBT)\n\nRatio\n2030 Target Maximum\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n36\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##LIFE CYCLE ASSESSMENTS\n\nBased on our initial cradle-to-gate LCAs, \nwe estimate that our brine-based lithium \ncarbonate production in Chile has about \ntwo times lower carbon footprint than our \nrock-based lithium hydroxide production \nin Australia (9.2 versus 4.7 kg CO2e/kg \nproduct). The distribution over scope 1, 2 \nand 3 is very different for brine-based and \nrock-based operations.\n\nGlobal warming potential (GWP-100), \ncommonly referred to as the carbon \nfootprint, of Albemarle’s Chilean brine-\nbased lithium carbonate is dominated by \nraw materials (~60%), primarily related \nto the amount of energy required to \nproduce the soda ash used in the lithium \nconversion process. The remaining 40% of \nthe footprint is primarily energy (~25%) \nand transportation of raw materials and \nconcentrated brine (~15%). Note that \nonly 5% of the footprint is related to \noperations in Salar de Atacama. The Salar \nproduction facility uses passive solar \nenergy for brine concentration which has \na zero footprint in an LCA.\n\nLife cycle assessments (LCAs) help us to \nbetter understand the environmental \nfootprint of our products and to drive \nimprovements in product and process \ninnovation, sustainable procurement, \ninvestment decision making, and \ncustomer service. Our first LCAs, \ncompleted in 2021, related to rock-based \nlithium hydroxide and brine-based lithium \ncarbonate. Both studies were performed \nin accordance with ISO 14040/14044 \nstandards using primary data from our \nSalar de Atacama, La Negra, Greenbushes \nand Xinyu operations and design data \nfor the Kemerton production facilities. \nThe Universidad Católica de Chile1 has \nsimultaneously conducted a detailed LCA \nfor brine-based lithium carbonate in Chile \nusing Albemarle data and is expected to \npublish results separately.\n\nLithium plays a critical role in the \ntransition to clean transportation. As a \nresult, many Lithium customers are \nespecially interested in the environmental \nimpact of our products. In the coming \nyears we will continue to refine and build \nLCAs for additional products across all \nour GBUs. We also plan to incorporate \nLCA requests into our sustainable \nprocurement process to better \nunderstand the environmental impact \nof our own suppliers. With transparency \nand collaboration across the value chain \nwe can collectively drive down GHG \nemissions. \n\n1  Conducted by Departamento de Ingeniería y Gestión de la Construcción (DITUC).\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n37\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##The carbon footprint of Albemarle’s \nAustralian rock-based lithium hydroxide \nproduction is dominated by energy (67%), \nprimarily related to the combustion \nof natural gas and consumption of \ngrid electricity. The remaining third is \nsplit between raw materials (14%), \ntransportation of raw materials, \nspodumene and waste (6%), mining (5%), \nprocessing (5%), and waste processing \n(2%). The conversion process at our \nKemerton production facility in Australia \nis inherently more energy intensive \nthan our brine conversion in Chile due \nto the nature of the process steps, such \nas calcination. On the other hand, the \nfootprint of the raw materials is lower \nthan for brine operations even after \nwe account for process emissions of \nCO2 from carbonates in the rock-based \noperations (5%).\n\nGWP-100 (‘Carbon Footprint’) of Lithium from Brine and Rock\n\n \n\n)\nt\nc\nu\nd\no\nr\np\ng\nk\n/\ne\n2\nO\nC\ng\nk\n(\n \n0\n0\n1\n-\nP\nW\nG\n\n12\n\n10\n\n8\n\n6\n\n4\n\n2\n\n0\n\nSalar de \nAtacama\n\nLa Negra\n\nSalar +  \nLa Negra\n\nTalison\n\nKemerton\n\nTalison + \nKemerton\n\nRaw Materials\nEnergy\nMining\nProcess\nTransport\nWaste\n\nScope 1\nScope 2\nScope 3\n\nDistribution of GWP by GHG Scope \n\n \n\n)\nt\nc\nu\nd\no\nr\np\ng\nk\n/\ne\n2\nO\nC\ng\nk\n(\n \n0\n0\n1\n-\nP\nW\nG\n\n10\n\n8\n\n6\n\n4\n\n2\n\n0\n\nBrine-based\n\nRock-based\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n38\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##WATER\n\nThe efficient and responsible use of water is a key component of our sustainability  \nstrategy. As such, we invest heavily in novel technology that allows us to increase \nproduction without increasing water intensity. Our goal is to reduce the intensity  \nof freshwater usage by 25% by 2030 in areas of high or extremely high water-risk –  \nnamely our lithium operations at La Negra and the Salar de Atacama in Chile, as well  \nas our JBC Bromine operations in Safi, Jordan. \n\nWater consumption is reviewed at GBU portfolio meetings on a quarterly basis, and we \ncontinually monitor our water withdrawal from rivers and lakes, groundwater, collected \nand stored rainwater, municipal water, and water obtained from other utilities. Our \nmeasurement of water use does not include brine (a source of bromine and lithium) \ndue to its extreme salinity, which makes it unusable as a freshwater source for human \nconsumption or agriculture. \n\nChile\nAt our La Negra operation, we have \ninstalled a thermal evaporator, a new \ntechnology that allows us to add \nproduction capacity of lithium carbonate \nwithout a corresponding increase in \nfreshwater usage. The thermal evaporator, \nbuilt at a cost of more than $100 million, \nuses technology used in desalination \nplants to produce high-purity water from \nour plant’s wastewater, which historically \nwas discarded to solar evaporation \nponds. The recycled water is used in our \nnew state-of-the-art process plant that \nproduces battery-grade lithium carbonate. \nAt full capacity, the thermal evaporator is \nexpected to reduce freshwater intensity \nby more than 30%. We are also currently \nstudying the opportunity to replace \nfreshwater use in Chile with desalinated \nseawater. \n\nJordan\nIn 2021, we brought online our Brominated \nFlame Retardant Co-Product Cleanup \nproject. Through our JBC joint venture, we \ninvested $20 million into a new technology \nthat facilitates recycling of a major co-\nproduct stream from our BFR production \nprocess. This project materially improves \nplant overall equipment effectiveness, \nreduces energy, raw material and GHG \nconsumption per metric ton of production, \nand reduces costs by $3 million per year. \nThis project also enables a subsequent \nproject named NEBO, a $30 million \ninitiative that will take a co-product stream \nand will convert it to a saleable product \nwithout the need for additional freshwater \nconsumption. NEBO is expected to reduce \nsite freshwater consumption intensity by \nmore than 10%. During 2021, our JBC joint \nventure also began recovering water from \nreject streams. Once fully optimized, this is \nexpected to reduce the water intensity of \nthe production site by an additional 14%. \nTogether, these water reduction processes \nare of significant benefit in Jordan, which is \nthe second most water-scarce country in \nthe world.\n\nFreshwater Consumption\n\n3\n\n \n\nm\nn\no\n\ni\nl\nl\ni\n\nM\n\n \n\n6\n\n5\n\n4\n\n3\n\n2\n\n1\n\n0\n\nLithium\n\nBromine\n\nCatalysts\n\n2019\n2020\n2021\n\nWater Consumption by Risk Category\n\n5,000,000\n\n4,000,000\n\n3,000,000\n\n3\n\n \n\nm\nn\no\n\ni\nl\nl\ni\n\nM\n\n \n\n2,000,000\n\n1,000,000\n\n0\n\nLithium\n\nBromine\n\nCatalysts\n\n1 – Low\n2 – Low – Medium\n1 – Low\n3 – Medium – High\n2 – Low – Medium\n3 – Medium – High\n\n4 – High\n5 – Extremely High\n\n4 – High\n5 – Extremely High\n\n39\n\n2021 ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##USA\nAt our bromine production facility in Magnolia, the marsh water recycling pilot initiated \nin 2020 continued into 2021 and has shown promising results. The process involves taking \nstormwater runoff from our innovative artificial marsh system, treating it, and converting \nit to freshwater for use in our operations. During the pilot, we reduced the amount of water \ntaken from the underground aquifer by 20%. Based upon the completed pilot, a permanent \nrecycling process has been designed and is scheduled for startup in 2023. \n\nAustralia\nAt our Kemerton production facility, a Water Management Plan has been adopted to \nensure that the quality and quantity of surface water and groundwater that flow from our \nproduction facility are maintained relative to pre-development conditions to protect the \nreceiving environment. The Kemerton Water Management Plan focuses on surface and \ngroundwater management, temporary drainage, monitoring and implementation, and \nremediation measures. The plan was developed in synergy with the Kemerton South Water \nManagement Strategy, incorporating Water Sensitive Urban Design principles and taking \ninto consideration the significant hydrological constraints present in the area. In 2021, our \nKemerton production facility was a runner-up in the Chamber of Minerals and Energy’s \nSouth-West Ngwayir Award for sustainable water management planning.\n\n40\n\n2021 ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##WASTE\nIt is in the best interest of the environment and of our business for Albemarle to reduce waste by maximizing the \nrecovery of extracted minerals and recycling or re-using production by-products. This allows us to be good stewards of \nthe environment while also reducing our costs. \nUSA\nIn 2021, the team at our Magnolia \nproduction facility led an initiative to \nreduce the waste generated by the creation \nof off-spec products which typically occurs \nduring transition periods of startup or \nshutdown. The team worked on analyzing \nall off-spec materials to better understand \nhow these might be blended into the \nexisting production to turn a waste stream \ninto saleable product and prevent it \nfrom ending up in landfill. As a result, we \nhave been able to save $5 million at the \nMagnolia production facility and have \ndiverted 732 tons of waste. \n\nJordan\nAt our JBC joint venture, we have \ndeveloped several innovative process \nchanges to improve yield and reduce waste \nfrom our fire safety production process. \nThe TBBPA (tetrabrom) waste treatment \nunit started up in August 2021, and our \nfire safety yield improvement project is on \nschedule for commissioning and startup \nduring Q2 2022. Together these projects \nare expected to reduce hazardous waste \ngeneration at JBC by 60%, volatile organic \ncompound (VOC) emissions to air by \n80%, and the amount of raw materials \nused and GHG generated per metric ton of \nproduct produced.\n\nAustralia\nAt our Kemerton production facility, we are \nusing proprietary engineering and process \nknowledge benchmarking from similar \nmining operations locally and around \nthe world to undertake a preliminary \nassessment of all potential waste streams. \n\nAlso at Magnolia, our process technology \nteams have scoped a project to improve \nthe yield of an intermediate used in the \nproduction of SAYTEX 8010. This capital \nproject is scheduled for completion in Q4 \n2022 and is anticipated to reduce raw \nmaterial usage and GHG generation per \nmetric ton of SAYTEX 8010 produced.\n\nAt our Bayport plant, our process \ntechnology teams have been \nexperimenting with varying sizes of filter \ncloths to find better ways to capture \nsolids that are released when we wash \nour products. We are in the process of \nquantifying and verifying the results of  \nthe new filters, and we will report further \non our progress in the future. \n\nTailings\nWe have been working on aligning our tailings management with industry best \npractices at our Australian production facilities. Tailings, which consist of ground rock \nand process effluents, are a waste by-product that is generated in the extraction \nprocess and presents an environmental challenge regarding disposal. At our Talison \njoint venture mining operations in Greenbushes, Australia, a tailings retreatment \nfacility opened at the beginning of 2022.\n\nIn 2021, Albemarle was named an inaugural recipient of a Modern Manufacturing \nGrant as part of the Australian government’s Modern Manufacturing Initiative. The \nAUD $4.9 million matched funding will help us create a specially designed system \nto turn the lithium alumino-silicate tailings at the Kemerton plant into a recycled \naggregate and reduce the amount of material sent to landfill. Our goal is 100% \nrepurposed use in building materials. \n\n41\n\n2021 ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##RESOURCE STEWARDSHIP\nTwo of Albemarle’s key businesses, Lithium and Bromine, \ndepend and rely on the availability of natural resources, \nand we believe that, as stewards of the environment, it is \nour duty to manage those resources responsibly.\nMinerals\nAlbemarle manages mineral resources \ntransparently, both at our own production \nfacilities and at our joint venture facilities, \nto ensure good relationships with our local \ncommunities, governments, regulators, \nand other key stakeholders. For example, \nin the Salar, we monitor brine resources \nand report monitoring data to the relevant \nChilean authorities, as well as to the local \nand indigenous communities. We meet \nregularly with the communities to review \nthe data. In some cases, communities \nhave used funds provided by Albemarle \nto hire independent third-party experts to \ninterpret this data. At our MARBL, Talison, \nand JBC joint ventures, Albemarle has \nrepresentation on the respective boards of \ndirectors, providing oversight on how our \nminerals are being managed and ensuring \nthese operations comply with applicable \nlaws and regulations.\n\nAs part of our commitment to the \nconservation, preservation, and restoration \nof the Salar’s ecosystem, and as a symbol \nof the legacy we want to create, we \ninaugurated the first botanical nursery at \nour Atacama plant in Chile. The nursery, \nwhich is in one of the driest deserts in \nthe world will house up to 5,000 plants \nin climate-controlled environments \nthat simulate azonal conditions to help \nmaintain various botanical species. These \nplants, which will be irrigated using \nrecycled, treated water from our facility, \nwill eventually reforest the area and will \nhelp to ensure the preservation of the \ncultural and biological heritage of the  \nSalar de Atacama basin. \n\nWe continue to monitor flamingo \npopulations in the lagoons closest to \nour operations in La Negra based on a \nvoluntary agreement we made with local \ncommunities in 2016. These migratory \nbirds, which include three species, James, \nAndino, and Chilean, settle in the Peine-\nPunta La Negra lagoon systems during \ncertain times of the year. We have spent \nover $1 million to honor this commitment, \nwhich has resulted in an increase in the  \nbird population. At Silver Peak, our \nIntegrated Avian Management Program \ncontinues with the monitoring of migrating \nbirds and avian mortalities and also \nprovides guidance on the identification \nand implementation of measures for the \nprevention of bird fatalities.\n\nLand and Biodiversity\nAt Albemarle, we want to minimize the \nimpact of our operations on biodiversity. \nTherefore, it is important to us to preserve \nand restore natural habitats as best as \npossible. We work with local communities \nand other stakeholders to ensure we \nconsider protected land and species where \napplicable. Our commitments under IRMA \nalso require us to consider and mitigate \nany negative impacts of our operations on \nnatural habitats and sensitive ecosystems.\n\n42\n\n2021 ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##OUR PEOPLE,  \nWORKPLACE &  \nCOMMUNITY\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n43\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##SAFETY\n\nWe care about the health and wellbeing \nof our employees, contractors, suppliers, \nbusiness partners, and host communities. \nBy fostering a strong safety culture \nthroughout our organization, we are \ncommitted to ensuring that everyone goes \nhome safe and healthy every day. Keeping \neach other safe is a personal and mutual \nresponsibility that we take very seriously. \nWe operate our sites in accordance \nwith applicable health and safety laws \nand regulations. \n\nOur commitment to a safe work \nenvironment begins with our leadership. \nAlbemarle’s CEO, in tandem with our \nGBU Presidents, is accountable for our \norganization’s safety performance. \nTogether, they hold quarterly town \nhalls to report on our company’s safety \nresults. The Health, Safety & Environment \nCommittee of the Board provides \noversight of Albemarle’s safety program \nand meets with our Vice President, HS&E \nand Operational Excellence quarterly to \nreview our HS&E performance, safety \ntrends, safety audit results, and corrective \naction plans. \n\nOur safety management system is based \non the Responsible Care RC14001 chemical \nindustry program that integrates the \nAmerican Chemistry Council’s (ACC) \nResponsible Care requirements with those \nof ISO 14001, and the OSHA Process \nSafety Management standards. We have \nadapted these standards to develop a \nrobust and tailored program specific \nto Albemarle’s needs and that apply to \nboth our corporate headquarters and our \nindividual sites. Each of our sites employs \na HS&E manager or safety manager \n\nequivalent who leads a team of staff to \noversee and implement country-specific \nsafety policies and procedures and to \nprovide local safety resources. \n\nEmployees are required to complete \ntraining specific to safety and are expected \nto take proactive steps to identify and \nprevent workplace-related injuries and \nillness. Every shift change meeting begins \nwith the sharing of safety moments, led \nby site management teams, supervisors, \npeers, or contractors. Sites utilize an \nemployee-led, central safety committee \nthat reviews processes and procedures \nto identify areas of improvement. We \nalso have subcommittees that are \nformed around specific safety topics, and \nemployees are encouraged to join these \ncommittees to engage with safety matters. \n\nOur people are our most important asset, and our ambition is to build a diverse, equitable, and \ninclusive workplace focused on safety, mutual respect, development, and wellbeing.\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n44\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Safety Performance\nAlbemarle’s safety programs are designed \nfor continuous improvement of our safety \nperformance, and thus we continually \nwork to improve and enhance our safety \nprograms and procedures. We benchmark \nourselves against our ACC peers and have \nconsistently ranked in the top quartile \nfor our safety performance. In 2021, we \nsaw year-over-year progress that includes \nimprovements in injury rate (TRIR) for \nemployees, from 0.26 in 2020 to 0.19 \nin 2021, and we were recognized by \nthe ACC with Responsible Care Facility \nSafety Awards for our achievements at \nmany of our sites. It is important to note \nthat we treat our nested contractors the \nsame as our employees, holding them to \nthe same standards and incorporating \nthem into our safety programs and \ninitiatives. That stated, we recognize \nan increase in TRIR this year for nested \ncontractors and are supporting focused \nsite efforts on contractor safety. We will \n\nbe staffing a corporate Contractor Safety \nposition within the HSE group to drive \nimprovement in our global contractor \nmanagement program. Our goal is to \nattain zero incidents and to consistently \nrank among the top decile of our peers. \n\nIn 2021, we continued to focus on our key \nsafety programs such as our Life Saving \nRules, which are comprised of the eight \nmost critical safety procedures that must \nbe followed and that are designed to \nprotect the lives of our employees and \ncontractors. We have seen the benefits \nof this program through leading indicator \ndata including safe work permit audit \nresults. While we are pleased with the \nresults that we have been able to achieve \nwith our Life Saving Rules, our goal is \nultimately to reduce the instances that \nnecessitate the application of these rules \nin the context of high-risk activities as we \nwork towards our goal of zero incidents. \n\nTotal Recordable Injury Rate (TRIR) Employees and Contractors\n\n0.8\n0.7\n0.6\n0.5\n0.4\n0.3\n0.2\n0.1\n0\n\n4\n6\n0\n\n.\n\n9\n5\n0\n\n.\n\n5\n7\n0\n\n.\n\n5\n5\n0\n\n.\n\n6\n3\n0\n\n.\n\n2\n2\n0\n\n.\n\n9\n2\n0\n\n.\n\n4\n.1\n0\n\n2017\n\n2018\n\n2019\n\n2020\n\n1\n3\n0\n\n.\n\n9\n1\n.\n0\n\n2021\n\nEmployees\nContractors\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n45\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Energy Wheel\n\nEnergizing SCAN\nIn our effort to achieve zero safety incidents, \nwe deploy our SCAN (Survey, Consider, \nAct, and Notify) hazard recognition and \nmitigation tool daily. This tool teaches \nemployees to stop, think, and identify \npotential hazards before they become \nincidents and to communicate to \nmanagement any hazards that may require \nlong-term solutions. In 2021, we enhanced \nour SCAN tool by integrating an external \ntraining program that focuses specifically \non energy hazard recognition. The program \nis based on the premise that hazards are \ndefined by exposure to one or more of \n10 distinct energy forms such as gravity, \nmotion, electrical, etc. Energy-based hazard \nrecognition involves using the Energy \nWheel to guide the scanning of dangerous \nwork environments and is intended to be \nused as a prompt for the brain to consider \nsome hazards that might otherwise go \nunnoticed. We look forward to seeing this \ntool rolled out globally in 2022. \n\nIn 2021, we piloted a new incident \nmanagement, near miss management, \nand leading indicator management system \nthat dovetails with our Manufacturing \nExcellence Management System (MEMS). \nWe anticipate roll-out across the company \nin 2022. Additionally, we are building \ncustom dashboards to help us monitor \ndata, conduct gap analyses, and implement \nplans for continuous improvement. We \nlook forward to enhanced reporting on our \nsafety data, such as near misses and other \nleading indicators in future reports. \n\nWe conduct regular audits of our HS&E \nprograms at our global sites. Due to travel \nlimitations imposed by the pandemic in \n2021, we created a hybrid model to allow \nus to proceed with our audits and to allow \nus to share safety best practices among \nour sites. We will continue to improve our \naudit process and, after travel limitations \ndue to the pandemic are lifted, we envision \nincorporating best practices from this \nhybrid audit process into our in-person \naudit process.\n\nENERGY\nWHEEL\n\nSCAN in Action\n\nWhile performing SCAN, a bromine bottle-filling operator at our \nBaton Rouge Process Development Center realized there was a \nbetter and safer way to fill bottles from the bromine storage tank. \nWorking collaboratively with the safety and engineering teams, \nthe box in which the bottles are filled was replaced with a new \ndesign that included adjustments to the height and accessibility \nof the box and the position of the bromine feed lines. This \ncreated a more ergonomically correct position for the operator \nand a safer filling environment.\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n46\n\n     Chemical               Temperature                 Gravity                     Motion                    Mechanical Biological              Radiation                       Sound                      Pressure                   Electrical\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Future of Work\nFuture of Work is our new human resources \nframework that supports the Albemarle \nWay of Excellence operating model, our \ncore values, our Code of Conduct, and our \ncommitment to DE&I and Sustainability. \nThrough this framework, we strive to \noptimize employee success and deliver a \nhigh-performance culture by:\n• \n\n Embracing workplace flexibility while \nbalancing business needs\n Investing in people, processes, and \ndigital tools to improve employee \nproductivity and customer \nsatisfaction\n Designing collaborative workspaces\n Engaging employees, encouraging \ncollaboration, and recognizing \ncontributions\n Offering benefits that maximize \noverall employee wellbeing\n\n• \n\n• \n• \n\n• \n\nIn 2021, we took a phased approach \nto returning to the office. Utilizing an \nemployee survey, we determined that our \nworkforce favors a highly flexible work \nenvironment with partial or full remote \ncapabilities. As a result, we reviewed each \ntype of role to assess suitability for remote \nor hybrid working, and we implemented \nnew guidelines for work post-pandemic \nthrough our Remoteability Framework. We \nare also researching ways to reconfigure \nour offices to reflect the changes in the \nway we work and expect to introduce \nhoteling and workspaces designed for \nenhanced collaboration.\n\nThe COVID-19 pandemic continues to be a challenge \nas we manage through the various waves of infection that \naffect each part of the world in differing ways and \nat different times.\n\nAt the onset of the pandemic, we deployed Albemarle’s Special Event Management \nPlan (SEMP), which guides our response to extraordinary and unforeseen events. \nWe moved swiftly to create a global team to manage and implement COVID-19 \nsafety protocols to keep our employees, business partners, and communities safe. \nThroughout 2021, we continued with mask, handwashing, and social distancing \nrequirements as well as contact tracing. \n\nWe provided COVID-19 testing and, as vaccines became available, we encouraged \nvaccination. Wherever possible, we provided financial incentives for vaccination \namong our workforce and provided vaccines to family and community members and \ncontractors onsite at our facilities. As of year-end 2021, approximately 80% of our \nworkforce was vaccinated.\n\nIn our remote indigenous communities in Chile, we implemented very strict protocols \nregarding the interaction between our employees and the overall community. \nWe wanted local residents to feel safe that when workers were transported from \nsurrounding communities, or flying in from the capital city of Santiago, there would \nbe minimal contact with community members. All Albemarle employees were \nrequired to adhere to strict reporting procedures and were mandated to remain at \nhome at the slightest sign of illness. \n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n47\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Connecting Our Employees \nThrough Technology\n\nDuring the pandemic, we accelerated the introduction of technology to support our \nemployees working remotely. We also introduced technology to facilitate virtual interaction \nand collaboration when face-to-face engagement was not possible. For example, employees \nat our manufacturing sites were equipped with smart helmets that featured cameras to \nenable site audits, which normally take place in person.\n\nHealth and Wellbeing\n\nAt Albemarle, we recognize the additional strain that the pandemic has placed on \nour workforce, regardless of location or work function. In 2021, we made significant \ninvestments in our health and wellbeing programs. We introduced an enhanced \nglobal Employee Assistance Program (EAP), which provides a confidential support \nservice for employees experiencing personal difficulties, and we introduced mental \nhealth days. We rolled out Microsoft Viva, a digital platform that helps employees \nand employers navigate the complexities of working from home. Viva provides \nemployees with confidential insights into their productivity, visible only to the \nemployee. Viva also includes features such as reminders that prompt employees to \ntake a break during the workday. \n\n48\n\n2021 ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##DIVERSITY, EQUITY  \nAND INCLUSION\n\nWe are committed to building a diverse, \nequitable, and inclusive workplace \nwhere everyone feels valued. We know \nthat organizations that have a diverse \nworkforce and inclusive culture are more \ninnovative and are better positioned to \nattract and retain talent. For a global \ncompany like Albemarle, our success \ndepends on our ability to employ \npeople of different genders, ethnicities, \nsexual orientations, ages, and cultural \nbackgrounds. Our aim is to create an \ninclusive culture by leveraging diverse \nperspectives, backgrounds, skills, and \ntalents to foster a sense of belonging. We \nactively work to remove systemic barriers, \nand we challenge and respond to bias and \ndiscrimination within our workplace. \n\nIn 2021, we released our DE&I Strategic \nPlan. This plan provides a blueprint for \nmeasurable actions that will help us \nintegrate diversity, equity and inclusion  \nin our strategic decision-making, enhance \norganizational effectiveness, and meet \nour future challenges and needs. Through \nindividual and collective responsibility \nfrom all employees, we can promote \ndiversity, equity and inclusion as a vital \nand prominent part of the fabric and \nculture of Albemarle. The plan relies on \nour leadership, managers, and supervisors \nin all business units, functions, and \nlocations to assume direct responsibility \nfor implementation. \n\nUnder the leadership of our Vice President \nof Culture, we have reviewed our hiring \nand HR processes with a DE&I lens and \nadded DE&I performance goals to our \npeople leaders. Managers are required \nto present diverse candidate slates and \nhave diverse interview panels for open \npositions as part of the hiring process. \nThese performance goals and practices \nhelp us to be more accountable in \nbringing diversity into our hiring practices.\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n49\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Driving Diversity Through Our CONNECT Groups\nWe also expanded our Employee Resource Groups (ERGs) called CONNECT groups and \nleveraged the groups to drive various initiatives around DE&I throughout the organization.\n\nCONNECT groups promote an atmosphere of inclusion and encouragement, where every \nemployee’s voice is heard. Heritage Month Activities – \n \n\n cultural education and awareness, communication skills, valuing differences, breaking \ndown barriers to inclusion, membership campaigns\n\n2.  Career Development – \n \n\n leadership skills, networking, mentoring, guest speakers, increased access to company \nleaders, and talent development resources\n\n3.  Attracting Talent – \n \n\n support for the company’s diversity recruiting efforts, support for onboarding and \nretention, association partnerships, supplier diversity recommendations\n\n4. Community Outreach – \n \n\n contribute to the communities where we live and work via strategic alignment with one \nor two preferred non-profits\n\nIn 2021, our CONNECT groups provided learning opportunities for our employees through \nseveral events such as Black History Month, International Women’s Day, Pride Month, and \nHispanic Heritage Month. \n\nDay of Understanding\nIn 2021, our CEO, Kent Masters, became \na signatory to CEO Action for Diversity \nand Inclusion, the largest CEO-driven \nbusiness commitment to advance DE&I \nin the workplace. In June 2021, we held \nour first Day of Understanding. Days of \nUnderstanding encourage organizations \nto host candid conversations throughout \nthe year to highlight and engage with \nreal-time issues and events as they arise. \nAs a signatory of CEO Action for Diversity \nand Inclusion, we are committed to \nproviding unconscious bias training, sharing \nbest practices, and engaging our Board \nof Directors in DE&I work, all of which \nwe initiated in 2021 and which we will \ncontinue to do going forward. \n\n“ If we are successful in  \nequity and inclusion, we \nachieve that sense of \nbelonging where everyone \nfeels comfortable and \ncontributes to the best of \ntheir ability. That’s going to \nmake Albemarle the best \ncompany we can be.” \n– Kent Masters, Albemarle \nChairman, President and CEO\n\nLearning and Leadership \nDevelopment \nIn 2021, we executed training and \neducation programs through our \nAlbemarle University. We will \ncontinue to offer training on additional \nsubjects in 2022. \n\nAs our company expands globally, it is \nimportant that we help our employees \ndevelop capabilities to manage an \ninternational workforce. Therefore, in \nalignment with the AWE, we are focusing \non creating a world-class employment \nbrand. Our vision is for Albemarle to be \nthe best employment experience for our \nemployees. We do this by ensuring that \nwe hire the right people for the right roles. \nWe invest in our employees’ personal and \nprofessional development and wellbeing \nto give them the tools they need to thrive \nand excel at Albemarle. We also take great \ncare to foster a supportive environment \nby taking a comprehensive approach \nto attracting, engaging, developing, \nmotivating, and retaining our talent and \nby providing pathways to leadership at  \nall levels of the organization.\n\nIn 2021, we took a concerted look at \nwhat is needed for the future success \nof our organization as we execute \nagainst our long-term strategy and our \nambitious growth plan. The result of our \norganizational assessment is leading us \nto apply a more strategic lens to our \norganizational structure, processes, and \ninvestments in global talent. Globally, we \nintroduced a new regionalized governance \nmodel to our organizational structure as it \nrelates to talent. We created local talent \nroles in recruiting, learning, and total \nrewards within different regions around \nthe world with the purpose of building \nlocal capacity and expertise, and we put \nin place an HR Transformation Team and \na Global Learning Council. Currently, we \nare in the process of building a Human \nResources Global Service Center to \n\nstandardize human resources processes \nand learning and development programs \nat our sites. \n\nCommitment to our investment in \ntalent begins at the highest leadership \nlevel with our Board. The Board oversees \nELT succession planning, including CEO \nsuccession planning, and meets annually \nto review and strengthen development \nplans. The Executive Compensation \nCommittee of the Board evaluates and \nprovides feedback on our executive \ntalent management strategy and plans, \nincluding oversight of the performance \nof our executive officers and Albemarle’s \nperformance related to workforce \ndemographics, progress, and goals aimed \nat attracting and retaining top talent. \n\nOur ELT is accountable for enterprise \npeople strategy aligned with Albemarle \nbusiness strategy that builds the \norganizational capability needed for \nfuture growth. This includes providing \nguidance on human capital and leadership \ndevelopment investments, setting the \ntalent agenda, approving the learning \nand leadership development budget, and \nputting in place a governance structure \nthat will scale to support our ambitions \nand goals. In 2021, the commitment to \ntalent development and building workforce \ncapability resulted in our ELT approving \na significant increase in the enterprise \ntraining budget, including hiring a full-time \ninstructional designer and interactive \nlearning developer and creating a new role \non the Albemarle Leadership Team (ALT) \nfor Organizational Effectiveness. \n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n51\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Starting in 2021, our ELT manages our \nhigh potential talent collectively as a \nleadership team via a dynamic talent \nprocess; guiding principles and working \nnorms that include: \n• \n\n Highlighting open roles and \ndevelopmental opportunities in \nleadership meetings\n Providing opportunities for key talent \nto profile their impact on the AWE\n Getting to know pipeline talent being \nmentored for executive roles\n Facilitating cross-functional role  \nand talent movement \n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\nUltimately, the leadership team’s \nobjectives are to create the oversight \nand visibility that encourages active and \nequitable sponsorship and to intentionally \nand proactively plan for building \nleadership capability that underpins  \nour values.\n\nInsights from this important work are \nmade available to employees to enable \ntheir career development journeys. For \nexample, as part of our annual executive \ntalent review and succession planning \nprocess, we identify the most critical and \nvalue-generating roles at Albemarle. At \nthe same time, employees express career \naspirations through Career Profiles and \nin discussions with their manager. One \nresource in development that aligns roles \nand interests is a learning paths playbook \nof the skills and abilities that lead to \nexcellence at Albemarle. This resource \nwill give employees and people leaders a \nclear understanding of the evolving needs \nof their current roles and the experiences \nneeded to advance to new positions \nwithin the organization that align with \ntheir career ambitions.\n\nEmployee Growth and \nDevelopment\nAlbemarle provides training and \ndevelopment on a wide variety of topics, \ndelivered through various channels, and \nadapted to each employee’s specific role. \nOur robust technical training program, \nbased on location and business unit, \nensures that everyone has the necessary \nskills to perform their job in a safe and \nefficient manner. For example, our Safety \nSkills series offers a collection of 125 \ne-learning manufacturing safety courses \nand sees 21,000 course completions \nannually. Albemarle University facilitates \nour mandatory training requirements \nsuch as training on our Code of Conduct, \ncybersecurity, safety, and DE&I and \nprovides a full suite of professional \nand leadership development modules \nto support our employees’ upskilling \nefforts towards their ambitions to further \ntheir careers. In 2021, we expanded the \nnumber of learning modules available in \nAlbemarle University to 18,000+ through \nthe add-on of LinkedIn Learning and we \ncontinued to provide most of our learning \nprograms on our digital platform after \npivoting to virtual learning in 2020. \n\nLeadership Development\nIn 2021, we enhanced our leadership \ndevelopment opportunities. Leadership \ndevelopment is critical for our succession \nplanning, and we take both a formal \nand informal approach to leadership \ndevelopment. We relaunched a \nglobal leadership program, Leading \nfor Improved Performance, aimed at \nfrontline supervisors and managers \namong our manufacturing workforce. \nThis global, regionalized management \ndevelopment program, designed to \nembed manufacturing excellence \nleadership and accountability principles \nacross sites is delivered in four different \nlanguages. Select sites have also piloted \na new leadership offering, Supervisor \nBootcamp, that accelerates the abilities \nof incoming frontline supervisors to take \nfull ownership of the duties of their role, \nstarting from day one on the job. Our \nAlbemarle Leadership Program aimed at \nmid-career managers was well received \nwith over 380 employees who took \nadvantage of the program in 2021. In \n2022, we will add an emerging leaders \nprogram, Elevating Leader, targeting \naspiring leaders and current leaders who \ndesire to advance in the organization, \nexpand their global networks, and gain \ncross-functional leadership visibility.\n\n18,000+\n\nlearning modules available through Albemarle University\n\nElevate Women\nTo increase the number of women \nleaders in our organization, we have \nplaced emphasis on career development \nprograms aimed at our female workforce. \nIn 2021, we launched our Elevate \nWomen program with 80 women who \nparticipated in the first cohort, and we \nkicked off three additional cohorts, adding \n60 more women across the globe to the \noverall program. The program is unique \nin that it does not restrict participation \nby leadership level – it is open to all \nwomen. Participants work in teams over \nfour months to complete action learning \nprojects featuring complex problems \nfacing Albemarle that were selected \nby senior leadership as important to \nthe success of the organization. As the \ncapstone of the program, teams propose \ntheir recommendations and solutions \nto our ALT. We also delivered training \nand development sessions through our \nemployee CONNECT groups.
