As a global market leader \nwith durable competitive advantages, we \nhave a track record of realizing economic \nvalue for our shareholders through strong \nfinancial performance and a positive  \nreturn on investment. \n\nAlso in 2021, in line with our Climate \nStrategy and at the request of Albemarle \nshareholders and some of our customers, \nwe filed disclosure under CDP for the first \ntime. The CDP is a global framework that \nhas become the de facto international \nstandard for reporting on environmental \nimpacts for use in financial decision-\nmaking. The CDP provides Albemarle \ninvestors and other stakeholders with \ncritical environmental data around climate, \nwater, and supply chain infrastructure  \nto integrate sustainability into the \ninvestment process. In 2022, we will \nfurther expand our CDP disclosure.  \nWith the filing of our 2021 annual report, \nwe also disclosed against the SEC’s \nRule S-K 1300, intended to improve the \nreliability of information to investors \nregarding property disclosures for mining \nregistrants and harmonize disclosures with \ninternational reporting standards. \n\nThroughout 2021, we continued to take \na prudent and disciplined approach to \nthe management of our global, best-in-\nclass asset portfolio while focusing on \noperational excellence to drive investment \nreturns. Our balance sheet was bolstered \nby strong margins and cash flow, giving \nAlbemarle the financial flexibility to \nsupport our long-term growth strategy. We \nmaintained our Investment Grade credit \nrating based on our financial strength and \nour growth and earnings potential. As \na result, both debt and equity investors \nshowed a strong interest in Albemarle, and \nwe were able to raise ~$1.5 billion through \nour equity offering. \n\nInternal Audit \nAlbemarle’s Internal Audit team is a  \nkey function of our ERM program. There \nare several inputs considered during the \ndevelopment of our annual audit  \nplan, including: \n• \n\n Strategic objectives and key \ninitiatives\n Key risk factors as disclosed in  \nour Form 10-K \n Internal Audit risk assessment, \nincluding interviews with cross-\nfunctional Albemarle leaders\n ERM framework coupled with \ninternal and external risk information \n Direct input from the Internal  \nAudit team\n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\nEnterprise Risk  \nManagement\nAlbemarle’s Enterprise Risk Management \n(ERM) program clearly identifies and \ndefines risks that could significantly \nimpact our company’s shareholder value \non a sustained or permanent basis. Our \nERM program helps us to assess key risks, \nidentify gaps, and develop and implement \nrisk mitigation efforts. This information \nis then integrated into our annual and \nlong-range planning processes. We look at \nquantitative and qualitative factors to rate \neach identified risk regarding severity and \nlikelihood to determine which risks should \nbe prioritized. We also pressure test our risk \nmitigation and management activities with \na broad group of relevant stakeholders. \n\nAlbemarle’s Vice President, Audit and \nRisk Management and the Enterprise Risk \nManagement Committee, comprised of \nmembers of the ALT, oversee our ERM \nprogram and periodically reassess our key \nrisks considering a constantly evolving \nbusiness context and risk landscape.  \nIn 2021, we identified 10 top enterprise \nrisks: execution of large and complex \ncapital projects, catastrophic incidents, \ncybersecurity, external risks to our \nstrategy, geopolitical risks, compliance, \nregulatory pressure, talent, supply chain, \nand shareholder activism. \n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n62\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Managing Geopolitical Risk\nAs a global company that derives over 75% \nof our profits from outside North America \nand with facilities and offices spread over \nfive continents, geopolitical events can \nsignificantly affect our business. These risks \ncan include changes in host country access \nto natural resources, proximity to countries \nin turmoil, developments in government \npolicy decisions, changes ahead of \nelections and regime changes, operating \nin environments where corruption is \npresent, and understanding and managing \nlocal perceptions of foreign operators. \nWe are also faced with asymmetric tax \nand regulatory regimes around the world, \nwhich adds a layer of complexity to the \nmanagement of our risks.\n\nWe proactively monitor regulatory \nand legislative initiatives and changes \nthat have an impact on our business by \nengaging governments, key stakeholders, \nand communities. A key aspect of our \nmitigation strategy is the diversification \nof our resources and conversion capacity \nthrough the acquisition of resources and \nthe building and acquisition of plants \nin different jurisdictions, spread across \nseveral continents. \n\nManaging Cyber Risk\nOne of our top 10 risks, cybersecurity risk \nis increased as employees continue to work \nremotely due to the pandemic. As such, the \nintegrity and security of critical business \nprocesses and information is a key area of \nfocus for our ELT and Board. \n\nTo mitigate the possibility of a \ncybersecurity breach, our Chief \nInformation Security Officer oversees \nsecurity initiatives and protocols that focus \non IT governance and standardization \nand vulnerability management through \ncontinuous monitoring. This includes a \nthird-party security operations center \n(SOC) and cybersecurity engineers who \nprovide 24/7 network monitoring. We \ncontinuously implement improvements \nconsistent with the National Institute \nof Standards and Technology (NIST) \ncybersecurity framework and audit against \nthese standards, and we upgrade our threat \nintelligence systems on a routine basis. We \nhave a documents management program \nin place, which includes data loss and \nmanagement information protection. \n\nOur IT Department conducts periodic cyber \nresponse drills, and in 2021, we ran our first \nransomware risk exercise with our ELT to \nsimulate what would happen if our business \nbecame the victim of a ransomware \nattack. The exercise helped our ELT better \nunderstand their roles and responsibilities \nin the event of such an occurrence and \nwhat assets might be most at risk of \nattack. We intend to repeat this exercise on \na periodic basis. We have also put in place \ntechnology and infrastructure to support \nour remote workforce and ensure routine \ncommunications from leadership to remind \nemployees to be vigilant of cyber threats, \nand we conduct monthly employee training \non cybersecurity.\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n63\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Managing Talent Risk\nAs Albemarle continues to grow and \nexpand globally, it is more important than \never that we have the right complement of \npeople to drive our strategy forward. The \nExecutive Compensation Committee of the \nBoard considers human resources risks and \npotential risks relating to our employee \n(including executive) compensation \nprograms.\n\nTo mitigate our talent risks, we have \nintroduced initiatives with a focus on \ntalent acquisition and retention, training \nand development, and succession \nmanagement, and we have invested \nsignificantly in training and development \nfor our employees. For examples of those \ninitiatives, please see the Our People, \nWorkplace & Community section  \nof this report. \n\nManaging Human Rights Risks\nAs a global company operating in the \nextractives industry, Albemarle knows the \nimportance of meaningful engagement \nwith its stakeholders and strives for \npositive human rights impacts, particularly \nin culturally sensitive locations such as \nChile and Western Australia where our \nsites are located on indigenous peoples’ \nlands. We recognize the human rights of \nour stakeholders, and we respect those \nrights through clear policy commitments, \na range of due diligence initiatives, formal \ncommunity agreements, and accessible \ngrievance mechanisms for reporting \nconcerns. Respecting the human rights \nof our employees, workers in our supply \nchain, members of our communities and \nother stakeholders represents our core \nvalues in action. \n\nWe recognize the human rights of \nour stakeholders as expressed in the \nInternational Bill of Human Rights and \nthe International Labour Organization’s \nDeclaration on Fundamental Principles \nand Rights at Work, and we acknowledge \nour responsibility to consider and address \nthe impact of our operations on the \nhuman rights of our stakeholders. We have \nexpressed our commitment in policies \nand procedures such as our Human Rights \nPolicy, Community Relations and Indigenous \nPeoples Policy, Global Labor Policy and \nHealth, Safety, Security & Environmental \nPolicy, among other standards. These \nstandards provide direction and guidance \nto our employees to ensure that our \nstakeholder and community engagement \nactivities support the fundamental \nprinciples of basic human rights.\n\nIn 2021, Albemarle engaged an external \nlegal firm to conduct human rights due \ndiligence to help us identify potential \nrisks at our Salar site in Chile and Xinyu \nand Meishan plants in China. We also \nintroduced a human rights risk lens to our \nprocurement process. In 2022, we plan to \nconduct human rights assessments in La \nNegra, Chile, and at our JBC joint venture \nin Safi, Jordan. \n\nManaging Climate Risk\nClimate change has been identified as one \nof the most pressing issues and risks  \nof our time. In 2021, we issued the \nAlbemarle Climate Strategy in which we \noutline our approach and responsibility to \naddress the impact of our operations on \nthe environment. We support the goals \nof the Paris Agreement to avoid climate \nchange by limiting global warming to well \nbelow two degrees Celsius and are pursuing \nefforts to limit it to 1.5 degrees Celsius. \nThis is not only the right thing to do, but it \nalso strengthens our competitive position, \nimproves our operational efficiency, and \ncreates value for our stakeholders.\n\nWe recognize that reducing our carbon \nfootprint is a multi-decade, continuous \nimprovement journey requiring \ninvestments in technology, infrastructure, \nand people as well as partnership with \nsuppliers and customers. Details of \nour approach to emissions reductions \ncan be found in the Natural Resource \nManagement section of this report. \nAlbemarle’s executive leadership and our \nBoard review progress on our climate \nstrategy on an ongoing basis, and the \nHealth, Safety & Environment Committee \nof our Board reviews targets, at least \nannually. The Audit & Finance Committee \nof our Board reviews climate change as it \nrelates to ERM, at least annually. \n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n64\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##BUSINESS ETHICS AND \nREGULATORY COMPLIANCE\n\naccountability. The Code, which is available \nin English, Dutch, German, Chinese, and \nSpanish, outlines the ethical expectations \nwe have of our employees, officers, and \ndirectors for the way they conduct their \nday-to-day business. In 2021, our Board \napproved minor updates to the Code, \nincluding a new introduction from our CEO. \n\nThe Code provides standards to deter \nimproper actions and promote honest, \nethical, and responsible conduct, \ncompliance with applicable laws and \nregulations, full, fair, accurate, and \ntimely disclosure in filings and other \npublic communications, prompt internal \nreporting of violations, and individual \n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n65\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##New joining employees are automatically \nassigned training which is relevant to their \nrole. insight and to help us \ndirect resources where they are needed. \nThis monitoring program is dependent on a \npublicly recognized analytics solution that \nour ethics and compliance team developed \nin coordination with our IT Department. \nWe use data sourced from internal systems \nand third-party suppliers to develop \nreal-time dashboards that are used by our \ncompliance team and senior management. \nOur monitoring program is supplemented \nby periodic ethics and compliance audits \nof Albemarle sites, non-controlled joint \nventures, and third parties. \n\nSpeak Up \nEmployees are required to speak up \nwhen they suspect activity that is \npotentially in violation of our Code of \nConduct or an applicable law. Concerns \ncan be raised anonymously and without \nfear of retaliation and can be reported \nto supervisors, the Chief Compliance \nOfficer or members of his team, the \nGeneral Counsel or members of the \nLegal Department, the Human Resources \nDepartment, or via our Integrity Helpline. \nThe helpline, which is operated by an \nindependent third party in a manner \nconsistent with the laws of the countries  \nin which we do business, is available  \n24 hours a day, seven days a week,  \nand in multiple languages.\n\nThe metric typically used as a proxy for \nmeasuring a company’s speak-up culture  \nis the number of employee reports per  \n100 employees. This includes unique \ncontacts (incident reports, allegations, \nand specific policy inquiry questions) from \nall reporting channels received during the \nperiod. In their 2021 Ethics & Compliance \nHotline and Incident Management \nBenchmark Report, Navex report an \nindustry median of 1.3 reports per 100 \nemployees. In 2021, Albemarle received \n1.2 reports per 100 employees, down from \n1.3 in 2020. These figures exclude policy \ninquiry questions. The year-over-year \ndecline in reports is consistent with that \nexperienced by other companies and is \nmost likely due to Covid-19 pandemic-\nrelated work restrictions.\n\nConflicts of Interest\nAlbemarle respects the privacy of its \nemployees, and their right to pursue \noutside activities and interests. When \npotential conflicts of interest arise, we ask \nemployees to take appropriate steps to \nmanage the risks arising from them. This \nincludes discussing a potential conflict with \ntheir supervisor, registering the conflict \nusing an online tool managed by Global \nEthics & Compliance, and respecting  \nany commitments made with regards to \nthe conflict. \n\n1  The training season for those engaging with government officials extended into 2022 due to the establishment of an enhanced \nGovernment and Community Affairs Function. \n\nBribery and Anti-Corruption\nWe prohibit all forms of bribery and \ncorruption, whether by our employees, \nthird-party sales representatives, or \nanyone else acting on our behalf. This \nincludes making facilitation payments. In \naccordance with the UN Global Compact \nTenth Principle, Albemarle works against \ncorruption in all its forms.\n\nAlbemarle’s Anti-Corruption Policy \nprovides guidance on the types of  \nactivities that might constitute bribery,  \nthe scenarios in which bribery might  \narise, and Albemarle’s expectations  \nand requirements in those scenarios.  \nThe Policy is supplemented by tailored \nanti-corruption-related requirements \nthat are embedded in functional policies \nrelating to sales, procurement, government \nengagement, community engagement, \ncharitable donations, and commercial \nsponsorships. \n\nAlbemarle takes a similar approach  \nwith regards to anti-corruption training, \nwith a mix of principle and risk-based \ntraining including:\n• \n\n Code of Conduct training for all \nemployees which typically includes an \nelement addressing anti-corruption\n General training focused on the \nCompany’s Anti-Corruption Policy\n Tailored core values/business ethics \ntraining (including anti-corruption)  \nfor employees engaging in  \nparticular functional activity  \n(e.g., sales, procurement, government \nengagement)\n Business ethics training (including \nanti-corruption) for “gatekeeper” \nroles such as inquire to cash and \ntravel and expenses\n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\nExcluding 2021 Code of Conduct training \n(which included reference to the Anti-\nCorruption Policy and anti-corruption \nrisk specific to charitable donations), the \nCompany provided tailored training to \nemployees engaged in procurement and \nengagement with government officials.  \nThe total number of employees identified \nas requiring training was 1,259 and the  \ntotal number of employees receiving  \nsuch training was 1,142 (91%).1 \n\nAlbemarle takes a multi-faceted approach \nto managing anti-corruption risk, which \nis not limited to snapshot site-based \nassessments:\n• \n\n Due diligence and pre-approval for \nuse of compliance-sensitive third \nparties such as distributors and \ngovernment-facing suppliers, and \ncontinuous monitoring of transactions \ninvolving such third parties. In 2021, \nAlbemarle extended its third-party \ndue diligence to include other types of \nsuppliers who present elevated anti-\ncorruption risk\n Due diligence and pre-approval \nof compliance payments such as \ncharitable donations, community \nproject contributions, and commercial \nsponsorships\n Pre-approval for gifts and hospitality \nabove a specified threshold and \nmonitoring of employee expenses\n Global anti-corruption risk \nassessment as part of the company’s \nbroader ERM program\n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\nThis is supplemented by periodic site \naudits, which include anti-corruption. \nIn 2021, three site audits (9%) were \nconducted by Internal Audit (percentage \ncalculated based on 32 site count).\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n67\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##External Engagement\nAlbemarle plays an active role in the broader ethics and compliance community. \nAlbemarle’s Chief Compliance Officer is a member of the Compliance Week Advisory \nBoard and a member of the teaching faculty of the Practicing Law Institute. Albemarle’s \ncompliance officer for the Europe, Middle East, India, and Africa region is a lecturer on \nbusiness ethics at Erasmus University, Rotterdam, and a member of the supervisory  \nboard of the Stichting Register Arbeidsdeskundigen.\n\nRegulatory Compliance and Government Affairs \nAlbemarle’s Global Product Stewardship Team is responsible for product regulatory \nactivities and supports key Health, Safety & Environment (HS&E) initiatives. We strive to \nensure that Albemarle products are safe and compliant with all regulatory requirements \nthroughout their life cycle. \n\nThe global regulatory landscape for the specialty chemicals industry is complex and \nconstantly evolving. Albemarle employees responsible for managing regulatory affairs \nregularly engage with governments and regulators and monitor evolving regulations not \nonly to maintain compliance, but also to prepare for emerging regulations in support of our \nGBU expansion plans and to bring next generation products to the market. We also ensure \nthat our products have been tested and evaluated to identify any product safety hazards \nor risks to human health and the environment. In addition, we focus on communicating our \ncompliance appropriately by making certain that our product safety data sheets, labels and \nother forms of communication clearly identify and communicate hazards for their proper \nuse and safe handling.\n\nIn 2021, we formed our new Government and Community Affairs (G&CA) team led by the \nVice President of G&CA and comprised of subject matter experts. However, \nin most cases, we were able to perform \nsubstantially better than market.\n\nFollowing these actions, Albemarle \nonly saw an increase in delivery time of \n10-14 days, compared to the industry \naverage of 14-21 days during this period \nof disruption. In the past, we operated \naccording to a just-in-time delivery \nmodel for our supply chain inputs. In \n2021, we minimized supply chain shocks \nby ensuring a safety stock of key sole-\nsourced raw materials as appropriate to \nour productions processes. In addition, \nto better serve our customers, we stored \nproducts closer to key customer sites and \ndeveloped contingency shipping routes.\n\nIn 2021, we implemented strategic steps \nto help address these disruptions and \nto mitigate future risks. We also \nrationalized a network of more than  \n30 trucking companies down to five \nstrategic partners. Therefore, we established \na Distribution Safety Department \nto manage HS&E for our logistics \nsuppliers. Under the guidance of this \nnew department, we adopted the use of \na transportation management tool to \nmeasure and monitor the carbon footprint \nof our logistics suppliers. In late 2021, this \ntool was introduced globally for marine \ntransportation, and we will be rolling \nout the tool globally throughout 2022 \nfor all transportation modes. We also \nintroduced a fuel surcharge program that \nencourages our suppliers to reduce their \nenvironmental impact. \n\nWe are increasingly shifting from high-\ncarbon to low-carbon transportation \nmodes by moving more goods via rail as \na substitution for truck transport, and \nwe are shortening route distances where \npossible, as well as the number of delivery \nvisits per vendor to our sites. R&D in our Catalysts business \nrevolves around developing new \ngenerations of refining catalysts. Better \nperforming catalysts enable refiners \nto convert disadvantaged feedstocks \nwith higher efficiency into high-quality \ntransportation fuels. Today’s internal \ncombustion engines generating lower \nemissions of SOx and NOx, and with \nhigh fuel efficiencies, require these high-\nquality fuels. \n\nIn 2021, we launched a product portfolio \nthat is specifically aimed at enabling \nrefiners to process bio-feedstocks to \nproduce biofuels. These feedstocks present \ntechnical challenges in the traditional \noil refinery for which our catalysts offer \nsolutions. \n\nWe are also working on developing and \nrefining catalysts and catalyst solutions \nthat can contribute to the chemical \nrecycling of non-recoverable plastic waste \nwhich addresses some of the fundamental \nlimitations of physical recycling of plastic. \n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n73\n\nInnovation Case Study\nIn 2021, Albemarle introduced Next Generation KF 774 PULSAR™ \nClean Fuels Catalyst, a novel and innovative solution for the  \nco-processing of renewables. The KF 774 PULSAR™, developed \ntogether with Albemarle’s joint venture, Nippon Ketjen, is our newest \ncatalyst in a growing portfolio of Clean Fuels Technology catalysts. The \nco-processing of renewables brings significant operational challenges, \nincluding reduced cycle length and yield, higher H2 consumption \nand pressure drop control issues. In addition, biofeed contains solid \nimpurities that lead to gum formation. The Next Generation KF 774 \nPULSAR™ Clean Fuels Catalyst successfully addresses these critical \nissues and brings a highly innovative product to the catalysts market. \n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Innovating for the  \nCircular Economy\nOne of the most critical environmental \nresponsibilities we have is to recover and \nreuse precious resources. To this end, our \ninnovation team is working on chemistries \nthat will enable us to take scrap materials \nfrom the battery production and recover \nlithium from end-of-life batteries \nand re-inject these materials back \ninto our conversion plants to produce \nbattery-grade quality lithium. This type \nof recycling will position lithium as a \nreusable resource in the circular economy. \nWe are working with strategic customers \nand industry partners to access scrap and \nend-of-life lithium streams. \n\nInnovation in Our Lithium Business – Improved Resource \nUtilization, More Efficient Chemical Processes, and  \nAdvanced Performance Products \nWe pride ourselves on our technological expertise and innovation, which contribute to \nmore efficient and sustainable lithium extraction, purification, and conversion to high-\nperformance products. This includes process innovations that allow us to recover more \nlithium from every ton of rock that we mine or from each liter of brine that we pump. For \ninstance, improvements in extraction and purification technologies help us to increase \nyields from our conventional lithium resources while opening access to non-conventional \nresources in the future. At the same time, innovation includes new process technologies \nthat increase asset utilization and improve reaction yields, which drive higher lithium \nrecovery through to our products while minimizing waste streams. \n\nDownstream in the lithium value chain, as batteries become more precisely engineered, \nso must the lithium materials we produce. This is driving customer demand for more \nadvanced forms of lithium that enable both near-term improvements and farther-\nhorizon breakthroughs in lithium-ion battery performance. This trend offers tremendous \nopportunity to make gains in sustainability. For instance, by increasing battery energy \ndensity through novel forms of lithium we are helping to make electric vehicles safer and \nlonger range. \n\nCombined improvements in lithium recovery at our resources, process enhancements \nin our conversion plants, and advances in battery performance in end-use products are \nincredibly powerful levers for improving sustainability. For every ton of lithium that we \nproduce, these innovations are helping us reduce GHG emissions while realizing lower \nusage of energy and freshwater. \n\nFor every ton of lithium that we produce, these innovations are \nhelping us reduce GHG emissions while realizing lower usage of \nenergy and freshwater.\n\nHigh Performance  \nLithium Materials\nIn 2021, our R&D team worked on a \ntechnology called prelithiation, a novel \nform of introducing additional lithium \nto either the cathode or anode side of \na battery to make better use of all the \nactive battery components such as nickel, \nmanganese, and cobalt, and thereby \nincrease battery energy density by as \nmuch as 20%. \n\nPrelithiation works by offsetting the \nlithium that is lost irreversibly during \nformation reactions in the battery anode. \nThe need, and therefore value, of a \nprelithiation solution has become greater \nas anodes have moved towards higher \nenergy density silicon-modified carbon \ncompositions. In parallel, Albemarle \nscientists continue to advance high-\npurity lithium reagents that will enable \nsafer lithium-ion batteries by replacing \nconventional polymer separators with \nsolid ion conductors. At the same time, we \nare working on highly engineered lithium \nmetal anodes that could potentially \ndouble battery energy densities. These \ntypes of innovations will have a significant \nimpact on how far an electric vehicle \ncan travel per charge and will make a \ntremendous contribution to the greening \nof mobility.\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n74\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Localization of  \nBattery Production\nGovernments around the world have \nexpressed interest in developing more \nlocalized value chains for critical raw \nmaterials such as lithium, including \nlocalized production. As a global leader, \nAlbemarle is uniquely positioned with \nexisting operations in Asia-Pacific, North \nand South America, and Europe. Today, \nAsia dominates the lithium battery \nsupply chain, representing 86% of \nbattery production. Based on discussions \nwith our customers, we are analyzing \noptions to restart our spodumene mine \nin Kings Mountain, North Carolina, \nand the potential to build additional \nconversion assets in North America and \nin Europe. Longer-term, there is potential \nto unlock by expanding extraction from \nconventional resources, exploring non-\nconventional resources, and developing \nmaterial and process technologies that \nwill enable next-generation batteries. \n\nBattery Materials  \nInnovation Center\nIn June of 2021, we opened Albemarle’s \nBattery Materials Innovation Center \n(BMIC), a state-of-the-art battery \ntechnology lab at our Kings Mountain \nsite in North Carolina. The BMIC supports \nour lithium hydroxide, lithium carbonate, \nand advanced energy storage materials \ngrowth platforms. \n\nCell-building capabilities at the BMIC \ngenerate meaningful data for next-\ngeneration battery material design to help \nour customers deliver high-performing \ncost-effective batteries. The center has \nbeen equipped to enable the synthesis \nof new materials, material properties \ncharacterization and analysis, material \nscale-up capabilities, and material \nintegration into battery cells for \nperformance testing. The facility includes \na dry room with a multi-layer pouch \ncell line that can create cellphone-sized \nbatteries to demonstrate critical aspects \nof battery performance and accelerate \ntransition of new products to customers. \nThe lab is also developing lithium metal \nanode technologies that hold promise \nto increase battery energy density by as \nmuch as 50% through the introduction of \nsurface-engineered lithium foils less than \n20 microns in thickness, about one-fifth \nof the average thickness of a human hair.\n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n \n1\n2\n0\n2\n\n75\n\n\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Project AI helps us identify opportunities \nfor more efficiencies and also notifies \nplant operators before problems occur, \nthereby reducing plant downtime. These \nadvanced analytics are also an important \ntool for managing our environmental \nimpacts and specifically our GHG \nemissions. Our Bayport plant has already \nrealized $4 million annualized savings, \nand Project AI is now underway at our \nAmsterdam and La Negra sites, with \nan anticipated rollout at our Xinyu and \nMagnolia locations in 2022.\n\nAdvanced Process Controls, \nReal Time Optimization and \nOnline Analytical Technology\nWe are in the process of deploying \nAdvanced Process Controls (APC) coupled \nwith online process analytical technology \non selected Bromine processes at \nMagnolia. APC leverages empirical and \nphysics-based models to automatically \ndrive the plant to its optimum in real time \nevery minute of the day. APC is expected \nto drive material capacity increases, cost \nreduction and sustainability benefits. \nFollowing initial deployments on selected \nprocesses at Magnolia, the APC approach \nwill be copied to JBC in 2023. \n\nData Analytics \nAt Albemarle, we have built a world-\nclass data science team to help us \nturn tremendous amounts of data and \ninformation into insight to drive smarter \nand faster decisions. Our data science \nteam develops demand and supply \nforecasts that are specific to region, \nresource, application, and battery \nchemistry. Our analytics team combines \nforces with our resource and mining \nexperts when we look at new acquisitions, \nfor example, to better understand \nprospective sites and to ensure that we’re \nmaking intelligent investments. Teamed \nwith our R&D scientists and engineers, \nour data scientists build physics-based \nperformance models that help us \nanticipate the value of novel lithium \nmaterials, sometime even before we \ninvent them, thereby providing focus for \nour research efforts. These same models \nhelp our application engineers and New \nBusiness Development team position \nnew products where they create greatest \nmarket value.\n\nProject Albemarle Intelligence\nProject Albemarle Intelligence (Project \nAI) was rolled out at our Bayport facility \nin Texas in 2021. This multivariate \nmachine learning model gathers real-\ntime data from Albemarle’s distributive \ncontrol systems, laboratory information \nmanagement systems, our SAP system, \nand other areas in the company to \ncombine data and intelligence into one \nlocation. It allows us to do a detailed \nmodel analysis on how our plants can run \nin the most efficient way so that we can \nimprove quality, yield, productivity, and \nraw material consumptions and achieve \nprocess stability for more consistent \noperational processes. \n\nT\nR\nO\nP\nE\nR\n\n \n\nY\nT\n\nI\nL\nI\n\nI\n\nB\nA\nN\nA\nT\nS\nU\nS\n\n \n\nE\nL\nR\nA\nM\nE\nB\nL\nA\n 89\n\nPage 89\n\n96\n\n2021 ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##GRI STANDARD DISCLOSURE\nGRI 205: Anti-\ncorruption 2016\n\n205-1 Operations assessed for risks related to corruption\n\nPAGE NUMBERS\n\nRESPONSE\nIn accordance with the U.S. Department of Justice Criminal  \nDivision Memorandum on the Evaluation of Corporate Compliance \nPrograms, the Company takes a multi-faceted approach to \nmanaging anti-corruption risk, which is not limited to snapshot  \nsite-based assessments: \n(a) due diligence and pre-approval for use of compliance-sensitive \nthird parties such as distributors and government-facing vendors, \nand continuous monitoring of transactions involving such \nthird parties;  \n(b) due diligence and pre-approval of compliance payments such \nas charitable donations, community project contributions and \ncommercial sponsorships;  \n(c) pre-approval for gifts & hospitality above a specified threshold, \nand monitoring of employee expenses; and \n(d) global anti-corruption risk assessment as part of the Company’s \nbroader Enterprise Risk Management program. \nThis is supplemented by periodic site audits, which include anti-\ncorruption. In FY2021, 3 (9%) site audits were conducted by  \nInternal Audit (percentage calculated based on 32 site count). \nInherent corruption risk arises from the Company’s: \n(a) distributors selling to third-party customers; \n(b) vendors engaging with government officials on behalf of the \nCompany for the purposes of e.g. securing licenses/permits for new \ncapital projects or existing operations; and \n(c) employee engagement with government officials for the \npurposes of e.g. securing licenses/permits for new capital projects  \nor existing operations. \nThis inherent risk is assessed and managed through the above-\nreferenced due diligence/pre-approval activity and the Company’s \nbroader anti-corruption and business ethics program.\n\n205-2 Communication and training about anti-corruption policies \nand procedures\n\n2021 Sustainability Report – Business Ethics and Regulatory \nCompliance / Performance Data\n\nPage 67 / Page 91\n\nGRI 206: Anti-\ncompetitive \nBehavior hours \na week. Temporary employees are not eligible for benefits.\n\nChina: part-time employees receive the same benefits as full-time \nemployees, and temporary employees are only eligible for statutory \nsocial security benefits and supplemental insurance.\n\nChile: we do not employ part-time workers, and temporary \nemployees are only eligible for life insurance benefits.\n\nGermany: part-time employees system\n\n2021 Sustainability Report – Safety\n\n403-2 Hazard identification, risk assessment, and incident \ninvestigation\n\n2021 Sustainability Report – Safety\n\n403-3 Occupational health services\n\nPerformance Data\n\nPage 83\n\nPage 44\n\nPages 44–46\n\nPage 80\n\n403-4 Worker participation, consultation, and communication on \noccupational health and safety\n\nAlmost all of Albemarle’s U.S. sites are ISO/RC 14001 certified. As part \nof the certification process, each site must have a Responsible Care \nSteering Committee (RCSC), led by the plant manager for overseeing \nthe site’s Responsible Care Management System. The RCSC will \ninclude a cross-sectional representation of the site (salary, wage and \nany nested contractor organization). The RCSC will work with the site \nmanagement to set the site HSSE policies and procedures consistent \nwith the Corporate HSSE policies and procedures, to establish site \nspecific significant HSSE aspects along with the operation controls \nfor such aspects, to establish and monitor the HSSE objectives for \nthe site, and to routinely evaluate HSSE programs for the site. The \nsite RCSCs will meet at least four times per year (typically quarterly, \nbut some sites changed to monthly meetings) and they report \nannually to the Corporate RCSC on the status of their site-specific \nsignificant HSSE aspects and objectives. Germany requires that there \nbe a safety council (Arbeitsschutzausschuss – ASA) for the German \nsites, which meets at least four times a year. Representatives of the \nworkforce in this safety council are members of the works council \n(Betriebsrat) and the speaker of the safety advocates (Sicherheits-\nBeauftragte). The ASA safety council represents the total workforce \non the German sites. At the Amsterdam site, two special works \ncouncil commissions (safety, health & environment commission and \npersonnel commission) meet with management to discuss safety, \nhealth, environment and wellbeing, respectively, on a monthly basis. \nThese commissions represent the total workforce on the site. The \nlocation in Louvain-la-Neuve in Belgium has a ‘Comité de Prévention \net de Protection au travail’. The committee meets on a regular basis \nto discuss health and safety issues. In Chile, both production sites \nhave worker participation committees, which are required by the \nChilean government.\n\n99\n\n2021 ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##GRI STANDARD DISCLOSURE\nGRI 403: \nOccupational  \nHealth and Safety \n2018\n\n403-5 Worker training on occupational health and safety\n\n403-6 Promotion of worker health\n\n403-8 Workers covered by an occupational health and safety \nmanagement system\n\n403-9 Work-related injuries\n\nGRI 404: Training \nand Education 2016\n\n404-1 Average hours of training per year per employee\n\n404-2 Programs for upgrading employee skills and transition \nassistance programs\n\nRESPONSE\n2021 Sustainability Report – Safety \n\nPAGE NUMBERS\nPages 44–46\n\nPerformance Data\n\nPerformance Data\n\nPerformance Data\n\nPerformance Data\n\nPage 80\n\nPage 80\n\nPage 80\n\nPage 81\n\n2021 Sustainability Report – Investment in Talent\n\nPages 51–54\n\n404-3 Percentage of employees receiving regular performance and \ncareer development reviews\n\nPerformance Data\n\n405-1 Diversity of governance bodies and employees\n\nPerformance Data\n\n405-2 Ratio of basic salary and remuneration of women to men\n\nPerformance Data\n\n406-1 Incidents of discrimination and corrective actions taken\n\nAlbemarle has confirmed one incident of discrimination and had \none open investigation with allegations of discrimination during the \nreporting period. ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##REPORT OF INDEPENDENT ACCOUNTANTS\n\n \n \n\n \n\nReport of Independent Accountants \n\n \nTo the Board of Directors of Albemarle Corporation \n \nWe have reviewed the accompanying Albemarle Corporation (Albemarle) management assertion that the \ntotal energy consumption and greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions metrics (sustainability metrics) for the year \nended  December  31,  2021  in  management’s  assertion  are  presented  in  accordance  with  the  assessment \ncriteria set forth in management’s assertion. Albemarle’s management is responsible for its assertion and \nfor the selection of the criteria, which management believes provide an objective basis for measuring and \nreporting  on  the  sustainability  metrics.  Our  responsibility  is  to  express  a  conclusion  on  management’s \nassertion based on our review. \n \nOur review was conducted in accordance with attestation standards established by the American Institute \nof  Certified  Public  Accountants  (AICPA)  in  AT-C  section  105,  Concepts  Common  to  All  Attestation \nEngagements,  and  AT-C  section  210,  Review  Engagements.  Those  standards  require  that  we  plan  and \nperform the review to obtain limited assurance about whether any material modifications should be made \nto management’s assertion in order for it to be fairly stated. The procedures performed in a review vary in \nnature and timing from, and are substantially less in extent than, an examination, the objective of which is \nto  obtain  reasonable  assurance  about  whether  management’s  assertion  is  fairly  stated,  in  all  material \nrespects, in order to express an opinion. Accordingly, we do not express such an opinion. Because of the \nlimited nature of the engagement, the level of assurance obtained in a review is substantially lower than the \nassurance that would have been obtained had an examination been performed. We believe that the review \nevidence obtained is sufficient and appropriate to provide a reasonable basis for our conclusion.  \n \nWe are required to be independent and to meet our other ethical responsibilities in accordance with relevant \nethical requirements related to the engagement.  \n \nOur firm applies the Statements on Quality Control Standards established by the AICPA and, accordingly, \nmaintains a comprehensive system of quality control. \n \nThe procedures  we performed  were based on our  professional  judgment. In performing our review, we \nperformed inquiries, performed tests of mathematical accuracy of computations on a sample basis, read \nrelevant  policies  to  understand  terms  related  to  relevant  information  about  the  sustainability  metrics, \nreviewed  supporting  documentation  in  regard  to  the  completeness  and  accuracy  of  the  data  in  the \nsustainability metrics on a sample basis, and performed analytical procedures. \n \nGHG emissions quantification is subject to significant inherent measurement uncertainty because of such \nthings as GHG emissions factors that are used in mathematical models to calculate GHG emissions, and the \ninability of these models, due to incomplete scientific knowledge and other factors, to accurately measure \nunder  all  circumstances  the  relationship  between  various  inputs  and  the  resultant  GHG  emissions. \nEnvironmental and energy use data used in GHG emissions calculations are subject to inherent limitations, \ngiven the nature and the methods used for measuring such data. The selection by management of different \nbut  acceptable  measurement  techniques  could  have  resulted  in  materially  different  amounts  or  metrics \nbeing reported. \n \n\n \n\n \n\nThe  preparation  of  the  total  energy  consumption  metric  requires  management  to  establish  the  criteria, \nmake determinations as to the relevancy of information to be included, and make assumptions that affect \nreported information. The selection by management of different but acceptable measurement techniques \ncould have resulted in a materially different amount being reported. \n \nAs discussed in management’s assertion, Albemarle has estimated GHG emissions for certain emissions \nsources for which no primary usage data is available. \n \nBased on our review, we are not aware of any material modifications that should be made to Albemarle’s \nmanagement assertion in order for it to be fairly stated. \n \n \n\n \nCharlotte, North Carolina \nJune 2, 2022 \n \n\n \n \n\n \n\n \n\n \n \n \n\n105\n\n2021 ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##MANAGEMENT ASSERTION LETTER \n\nOverview\nWith respect to the total energy consumption and greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions \nmetrics (sustainability metrics) presented by Albemarle Corporation (Albemarle) in the \ntable to the right for the year ended December 31, 2021, management of Albemarle asserts \nthat the sustainability metrics are presented in accordance with the assessment criteria set \nforth below. Management is responsible for the selection of the criteria, which management \nbelieves provide an objective basis for measuring and reporting on the sustainability \nmetrics. Management is responsible for the completeness, accuracy, and validity of the \nsustainability metrics. \n\nMetric\nTotal Energy \nConsumption\n\nScope 1 GHG \nEmissions\n\nOrganizational Boundary \n• \n\n In accordance with the GHG Protocol (as defined below), Albemarle uses the \nfinancial control approach for determination of the organizational boundary \nfor reporting the sustainability metrics. This includes both leased and owned \nfacilities engaged in both production and non-production activities as well as joint \nventure arrangements under certain conditions (as defined below), and leased/\nowned vehicles. \n Under the financial control approach, joint ventures are included in the \norganizational boundary according to the equity share approach. The Salmag (Chile) \nand Safi (Jordan) joint ventures are deemed to be within Albemarle’s financial \ncontrol, and in turn, the emissions are included within Scope 1 and 2 based on their \nrespective share of equity in the operation. All remaining joint ventures are not \nwithin Albemarle’s financial control, and therefore, are excluded from Scope 1 and 2  \nemissions and the emissions from these joint ventures are included under Scope 3, \nCategory 15: Investments. Scope 3 GHG emissions are not within the scope of this \nmanagement assertion.\n Emissions of divested businesses are included on a pro-rata basis using prior year \ndata. Emissions from the Fine Chemistry Services business, which was divested on \nJune 1, 2021, are therefore incorporated on a 5/12th basis. \n New production facilities, which there were none in 2021, are included starting in \nthe year and month in which it first produces saleable goods.\n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\nMetric Quantity\n13.8 million Gigajoules (GJ)\n\n605 thousand metric tons \nof carbon dioxide equivalent \n(kt CO2e)\n\nDefinition of the Metric and \nAssessment Criteria\nDirect and indirect energy \nconsumed related to Scope 1 and \nScope 2 activities. \n\nDirect emissions of GHG \nfrom stationary and mobile \ncombustion. Stationary \ncombustion relates to combustion \nof fossil fuels, chemical process \nreleases, and fugitive emissions. \nMobile combustion relates to \nemissions from leased/owned \nvehicles.\n\nScope 2 GHG \nEmissions\n\nIndirect emissions of GHG \nfrom the use of purchased grid \nelectricity and steam. \n\nLocation-based:  \n348 thousand kt CO2e\nMarket-based:  \n294 thousand kt CO2e\n\nTotal Energy Consumption\n• \n\n Albemarle considers the principles and guidance of the Sustainability Accounting \nStandards Board (SASB) Chemicals Industry Standard Accounting Metric RT-CH-\n130a.1 to guide the criteria to assess, calculate, and report total energy consumption.\n Total energy consumption (in million gigajoule) is the sum of direct energy from \npurchased fuels (natural gas, liquid petroleum gas (LPG), gasoline, distillates, and \nfuel oil) and indirect energy from purchased grid electricity and steam. \n Energy is calculated by conversion to gigajoule of direct and indirect energy usage \nfrom Scope 1 and Scope 2 consumption data as further discussed in the Scope 1 \nand Scope 2 GHG Emissions sections below. Consumption data is then converted \nto gigajoule.\n The preparation of the total energy consumption metric requires management to \nestablish the criteria, make determinations as to the relevancy of information to \nbe included, and make assumptions that affect reported information. The selection \nby management of different but acceptable measurement techniques could have \nresulted in a materially different amount being reported.\n Estimated energy consumption accounts for approximately 1% of total energy \nconsumption. \n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\n106\n\n2021 ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##General GHG Emissions Considerations\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\n Albemarle considers the principles and guidance of the World Resources Institute \n(WRI) and the World Business Council for Sustainable Development’s (WBCSD) \nThe Greenhouse Gas Protocol: A Corporate Accounting and Reporting Standard, \nRevised Edition and GHG Protocol Scope 2 Guidance: An Amendment to the GHG \nProtocol Corporate Standard (together, the “GHG Protocol”) to guide the criteria to \nassess, calculate, and report GHG emissions.\n GHG emissions quantification is subject to significant inherent measurement \nuncertainty because of such things as GHG emissions factors that are used in \nmathematical models to calculate GHG emissions, and the inability of these \nmodels, due to incomplete scientific knowledge and other factors, to accurately \nmeasure under all circumstances the relationship between various inputs and \nthe resultant GHG emissions. Environmental and energy use data used in GHG \nemissions calculations are subject to inherent limitations, given the nature and the \nmethods used for measuring such data. The selection by management of different \nbut acceptable measurement techniques could have resulted in materially different \namounts or metrics being reported.\n GHG emissions are expressed in carbon dioxide equivalent (CO2e) emissions and \ninclude carbon dioxide (CO2), methane (CH4), nitrous oxide (N2O), and industrial \ngases, such as hydrochlorofluorocarbons (HCFC’s) and hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs). \nThe other GHGs of sulfur hexafluoride (SF6), perfluorocarbons (PFCs), and nitrogen \ntrifluoride (NF3) are not emitted by Albemarle’s facilities. Emissions data by \nindividual GHG is not disclosed as a majority of CO2e relates to CO2. Carbon dioxide \nequivalent emissions are calculated by multiplying actual or estimated energy, fuel, \nand refrigerant usage by the relevant emission factor taking into account the Global \nWarming Potentials (GWPs) of the compounds as defined by the Intergovernmental \nPanel on Climate Change’s (IPCC) Fifth Assessment Report (AR5 – 100 year). All \nemission factors are updated annually where applicable.\n\nScope 1 GHG Emissions\n• \n\n Albemarle tracks emissions from the stationary combustion of fossil fuels, the \nrelease of GHG emissions during chemical processes, and the release of fugitive \nemissions and mobile combustion related to emissions from leased/owned vehicles.\n Emissions from stationary and mobile combustion: \n• \n\n Consumption is measured based on production facility-level monthly (or \naggregate) third-party invoices of purchased fossil fuels (natural gas, LPG, \ngasoline, distillates, and fuel oil). \n\n Production facilities:\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\n Non-production facilities:\n• \n\n Consumption is estimated based on the actual square meter of office space \nin each location as reported by facility and office managers. The average \nenergy consumed per square meter of office space is based on publicly \navailable information for non-residential buildings. \n\n Emissions from Albemarle operated vehicle fleet:\n• \n\n Calculated based on the total number of leased/owned vehicles obtained \nfrom the fleet management team, the estimated annual average distance \ndriven per car based on publicly available average annual number of \nkilometers driven in 2020, and the average GHG emissions per kilometer \nbased on publicly available data of CO2 performance of new passenger cars.\n\n Emission factors used to convert the consumption of fossil fuels into GHG \nemissions at production and non-production facilities: United States (US) \nEnvironmental Protection Agency (EPA) Code of Federal Regulations, Title 40, \nChapter I, Subchapter C, Part 98, Table C-1: Default CO2 Emission Factors and \nHigh Heat Values for Various Types of Fuel (Last Modified: December 9, 2016).\n\n Emissions from chemical processes: \n• \n\n Estimated based on actual quantity of chemicals consumed which are known \nto release GHG emissions during the chemical process and dissolved CO2 in \nbrine. The GHG emissions are calculated on the basis of stoichiometry (chemical \nprocess) or measured content (CO2 in brine). The calculation outputs the \nquantity of CO2 generated by the process which is then converted to CO2e using \nthe relevant GWP.\n\n Emissions from fugitives: \n• \n\n Hydrofluorocarbons (HFC’s) and hydrochlorofluorocarbons (HCFC’s) are \nrelated to replenishment of purchased refrigerants during 2021. Refrigerant \nconsumption is calculated based on third-party invoices of purchased quantities \nof refrigerants. The GWP of the individual refrigerants is then used to convert the \nfugitives into CO2e. \n\n Estimated emissions from non-production facilities, the divested business, operated \nvehicle fleet, and chemical processes account for approximately 8% of Scope 1 GHG \nemissions.\n\n107\n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\n• \n\n2021 ALBEMARLE SUSTAINABILITY REPORT\x0c##PAGE_BREAK##Scope 2 GHG Emissions\n• \n• \n\n Albemarle tracks indirect emissions from the purchase of grid electricity and steam.\n Production facilities: \n• \n\n Electricity and steam usage data is obtained based on monthly utility invoices \nfrom third-party suppliers. Natural Language Processing¶

Extracting content by pages and sentences¶

  1. Only properly structured sentences are extracted. Sentences that start with a Capital Letter and ends with a period. Sentences that are less than 10 words or more than 50 words are ignored.
  2. Pages with less than 500 words are excluded from extraction. Would like to focus on pages with mostly text content. This should exclude pages like cover and last page. It should also exclude pages that are more graphical with short notes and comments.
In [25]:
def remove_non_ascii(text):
    printable = set(string.printable)
    return ''.join(filter(lambda x: x in printable, text))

def not_header(line):
    # as we're consolidating broken lines into paragraphs, we want to make sure not to include headers
    return not line.isupper()

def extract_sentences(nlp, text):
    """
    Extracting ESG statements from raw text by removing junk, URLs, etc.
    We group consecutive lines into paragraphs and use spacy to parse sentences.
    """
    MIN_WORDS_PER_PAGE = 500
    
    pages = text.split('##PAGE_BREAK##')
#     print('Number of Pages: {}'.format(len(pages)))

    lines = []
    for page in pages:
        
        # remove non ASCII characters
        text = remove_non_ascii(page)
        
        if len(text.split(' ')) < MIN_WORDS_PER_PAGE:
#             print('Skipped Page: {}'.format(len(text.split(' '))))
            continue
        
        prev = ""
        for line in text.split('\n\n'):
            # aggregate consecutive lines where text may be broken down
            # only if next line starts with a space or previous does not end with dot.
            if(line.startswith(' ') or not prev.endswith('.')):
                prev = prev + ' ' + line
            else:
                # new paragraph
                lines.append(prev)
                prev = line

        # don't forget left-over paragraph
        lines.append(prev)
        lines.append('##SAME_PAGE##')
        
    lines = '  '.join(lines).split('##SAME_PAGE##')
    
    # clean paragraphs from extra space, unwanted characters, urls, etc.
    # best effort clean up, consider a more versatile cleaner
    
    sentences = []
    pages_content = []

    for line in lines[:-1]:
        # removing header number
        line = re.sub(r'^\s?\d+(.*)$', r'\1', line)
        # removing trailing spaces
        line = line.strip()
        # words may be split between lines, ensure we link them back together
        line = re.sub(r'\s?-\s?', '-', line)
        # remove space prior to punctuation
        line = re.sub(r'\s?([,:;\.])', r'\1', line)
        # ESG contains a lot of figures that are not relevant to grammatical structure
        line = re.sub(r'\d{5,}', r' ', line)
        # remove emails
        line = re.sub(r'\S*@\S*\s?', '', line)
        # remove mentions of URLs
        line = re.sub(r'((http|https)\:\/\/)?[a-zA-Z0-9\.\/\?\:@\-_=#]+\.([a-zA-Z]){2,6}([a-zA-Z0-9\.\&\/\?\:@\-_=#])*', r' ', line)
        # remove multiple spaces
        line = re.sub(r'\s+', ' ', line)
        # join next line with space
        line = re.sub(r' \n', ' ', line)
        line = re.sub(r'.\n', '. ', line)
        line = re.sub(r'\x0c', ' ', line)
        
        pages_content.append(str(line).strip())

        # split paragraphs into well defined sentences using spacy
        for part in list(nlp(line).sents):
            sentences.append(str(part).strip())

#           sentences += nltk.sent_tokenize(line)
            
    # Only interested in full sentences and sentences with 10 to 100 words.
    sentences = [s for s in sentences if re.match('^[A-Z][^?!.]*[?.!]$', s) is not None]
    sentences = [s.replace('\n', ' ') for s in sentences]
    sentences = [s for s in sentences if (len(s.split(' ')) > 10) & (len(s.split(' ')) < 100)]

    return pages_content, sentences
In [26]:
report_pages, report_sentences = extract_sentences(nlp, report['content'])

Tokenization, Bigrams and Lemmatization¶

In [28]:
def run_NLP(content):

    def sent_to_words(sentences):
        for sentence in sentences:
            yield(gensim.utils.simple_preprocess(str(sentence), deacc=True))  # deacc=True removes punctuations

    # Define functions for stopwords, bigrams, trigrams and lemmatization
    def remove_stopwords(texts):
        return [[word for word in simple_preprocess(str(doc)) if word not in stop_words] for doc in texts]

    def make_bigrams(texts):
        return [bigram_mod[doc] for doc in texts]

    def make_trigrams(texts):
        return [trigram_mod[bigram_mod[doc]] for doc in texts]

    def lemmatization(texts, allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ', 'VERB', 'ADV']):
        """https://spacy.io/api/annotation"""
        texts_out = []
        for sent in texts:
            doc = nlp(" ".join(sent)) 
            texts_out.append([token.lemma_ for token in doc if token.pos_ in allowed_postags])
        return texts_out

    data_words = list(sent_to_words(content))

    # Build the bigram and trigram models
    bigram = gensim.models.Phrases(data_words, min_count=5, threshold=100) # higher threshold fewer phrases.
    trigram = gensim.models.Phrases(bigram[data_words], threshold=100)  

    # Faster way to get a sentence clubbed as a trigram/bigram
    bigram_mod = gensim.models.phrases.Phraser(bigram)
    trigram_mod = gensim.models.phrases.Phraser(trigram)

    # Remove Stop Words
    data_words_nostops = remove_stopwords(data_words)

    # Form Bigrams
    data_words_bigrams = make_bigrams(data_words_nostops)

    # Do lemmatization keeping only noun, adj, vb, adv
    data_lemmatized = lemmatization(data_words_bigrams, allowed_postags=['NOUN', 'ADJ', 'VERB', 'ADV'])
    
    return data_lemmatized

Using full text content in a page rather than full text content in a sentence here. A page defined as a document as per TFIDF calculation.

In [37]:
# Extract bi-grams names
words = bigram_tf_idf_vectorizer.get_feature_names()

# extract our top 10 ngrams
total_counts = np.zeros(len(words))
for t in bigram_tf_idf:
    total_counts += t.toarray()[0]

count_dict = (zip(words, total_counts))
count_dict = sorted(count_dict, key=lambda x:x[1], reverse=True)[0:30]
words = [w[0] for w in count_dict]
counts = [w[1] for w in count_dict]
x_pos = np.arange(len(words))
In [38]:
# Plot top 10 ngrams
plt.figure(figsize=(16, 6))
plt.subplot(title='30 most common uni-gram and bi-grams')
sns.barplot(x=x_pos,y=counts,palette='Blues_r')
plt.xticks(x_pos, words, rotation=90) 
plt.xlabel('N-grams')
plt.ylabel('tfidf')
plt.show()

Topic Modeling and Latent Dirichlet Allocation (LDA)¶

Evaluaton Metrics

  1. Perplexity: Captures how surprised a model is of new data it has not seen before, and is measured as the normalized log-likelihood of a held-out test set. Lower the better.
  2. Coherence Score: Measures score a single topic by measuring the degree of semantic similarity between high scoring words in the topic. Higher the better.

In the analysis, the model with the highest coherence score is selected as the optimal model.

In [39]:
# Create Dictionary
id2word = corpora.Dictionary(data_lemmatized)

# Create Corpus
texts = data_lemmatized

# Term Document Frequency
corpus = [id2word.doc2bow(text) for text in texts]

In [42]:
results = []
optimal_score = 0
optimal_model = None

for num_of_topics in tqdm(range(2,15,1)):
    
    result = {}
    
    # Build LDA model
    lda_model = gensim.models.ldamodel.LdaModel(corpus=corpus,
                                                id2word=id2word,
                                                num_topics=num_of_topics, 
                                                random_state=42,
                                                update_every=1,
                                                chunksize=5,
                                                passes=20,
                                                alpha='auto',
                                                per_word_topics=True) 

    coherence_model_lda = CoherenceModel(model=lda_model, texts=data_lemmatized, dictionary=id2word, coherence='c_v')
    
    if optimal_score < coherence_model_lda.get_coherence():
        optimal_score = coherence_model_lda.get_coherence()
        optimal_model = lda_model

    result['num_of_topics'] = num_of_topics
    result['perplexity'] = lda_model.log_perplexity(corpus)
    result['coherence_score'] = coherence_model_lda.get_coherence()
    
    results.append(result)
    
results = pd.DataFrame(results)  
results.set_index('num_of_topics', inplace=True) 

  0%|          | 0/13 [00:00<?, ?it/s]

cols = [color for name, color in mcolors.TABLEAU_COLORS.items()]  # more colors: 'mcolors.XKCD_COLORS'

cloud = WordCloud(stopwords=stop_words,
                  background_color='white',
                  width=2500,
                  height=1800,
                  max_words=50,
                  colormap='tab10',
                  color_func=lambda *args, **kwargs: cols[i],
                  prefer_horizontal=1.0)

topics = optimal_model.show_topics(formatted=False)

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(15,15), sharex=True, sharey=True)

for i, ax in enumerate(axes.flatten()):
    fig.add_subplot(ax)
    topic_words = dict(topics[i][1])
    cloud.generate_from_frequencies(topic_words, max_font_size=300)
    plt.gca().imshow(cloud)
    plt.gca().set_title(topic_names[i], fontdict=dict(size=16))
    plt.gca().axis('off')


plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0, hspace=0)
plt.axis('off')
plt.margins(x=0, y=0)
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

Closing Notes¶

  1. This is only a simple analysis that studies the ESG topics in only one ESG report. This study can be extended to more reports issued by the many companies across different sectors and industries.
  2. We can expect the number of topics to increase when more ESG reports are included in the study.
  3. Once relevant ESG topics are identified, then we can potentially calculate ESG scores by topics for all companies. Then we can assess and see whether such ESG score derived through NLP process correlates with the score given by rating agencies downloaded from yahoo finance.
